title: LP [2015]
summary: This is the third full-length release from Ren Schofield's electronic project named LP.

title: Wine Dark Sea
summary: The sixth solo release for the singer-songwriter was self-produced and includes contributions from Doug Wieselman and Indigo Street.

title: Wrangled
summary: The second full-length solo release for the Kentucky singer-songwriter features a guest appearance from Yelawolf and was co-produced with Oran Thornton.

title: Pick Me Up Off the Floor
summary: The seventh full-length solo studio release for the singer-songwriter features songs that were not included on 2016's Daylight Again.

title: Eye Contact
summary: The New York quintet release an experimental and electronic-heavy fifth album.

title: Scheherazade
summary: The first album in over a decade for the duo of Catherine Irwin and Janet Beveridge Bean features contributions from such artist as Sarah Balliet, Warren Ellis, Morgan Geer, and Evan Patterson.

title: Beyondless
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Danish post-punk band features a guest appearance from Sky Ferreira and was produced by Nis Bysted.

title: In Search of Harperfield
summary: The third solo release for the former Delgados band member was produced by her husband, Paul Savage.

title: Dead
summary: This is the second full-length studio release for the Edinburgh-based hip-hop trio of Alloysious Massaquoi, Kayus Bankole, and Graham Hastings.

title: Nothing Feels Natural
summary: The debut full-length release for the Washington, DC punk band was produced by Kevin Erickson.

title: The Besnard Lakes Are The Dark Horse
summary: Album number two for the Canadian indie-rockers is their first for Jagjaguwar.

title: Grinderman 2
summary: Nick Cave brings the experiences and sounds of his 30-year career to the table with the second release from his latest musical project since the Bad Seeds, with more of the trademark soaring piano, crunchy guitar, violins and mandolins to create an experimental new album.

title: Flying Dream 1
summary: The ninth full-length studio release for British alternative rock band Elbow was recorded at the Theatre Royal Brighton.

title: Out of My Province
summary: The third full-length release for the New Zealand singer-songwriter was produced by Trey Pollard and Matthew E. White.

title: The Return
summary: The debut full-length studio release for the Australian rapper features guest appearances from Alien, Blue Lab Beats, Boadi, Jace XL, Krown, Lori, Mandarin Dreams, SILENTJAY, Steam Down, Sunburnt Soul Choir, Thando, Mwanje Tembo, Theresa Mutale Tembo, Whosane, and Ecca Vandal.

title: Devour
summary: The fourth full-length release for Margaret Chardiet as Pharmakon was recorded live in studio by Uniform's Ben Greenberg.

title: Eyes on the Lines
summary: The latest solo release for the singer-songwriter is his first on the Matador label.

title: Whelm
summary: The debut full-length release for the British singer-songwriter was produced with Fabian Prynn.

title: Special Affections
summary: Originally released in 2010 on Secret City Records, the debut full-length album for John O'Regan of the D'Urbervilles is rereleased on Astralwerks.

title: Hidden
summary: The British rock band uses a vast variety of musical instruments and styles for its second album.

title: Uproot
summary: After several years in Spain, Jace Clayton returns to New York with his latest album of electronic mixes.

title: New Amerykah: Part One (4th World War)
summary: Erykah Badu's latest album was produced by 9th Wonder, Madlib, Mike "Chav" Chavarria, and Bilal.
After both rapping and producing on other artists' records, double-threat Blueprint finally combines his talents on his first solo disc. Aesop Rock, Illogic and Vast Aire guest.

title: Sung Tongs
summary: The Brooklyn-based collective (on this release, reduced to the duo of Avey Tare and Panda Bear) combine vocal harmonies, a pair of acoustic guitars, and diverse influences into a unique sound on this latest release.

title: Escondida
summary: 'Escondida' marks the first solo studio disc for the Texas-born folk singer-songwriter who also co-founded the Canadian group The Be Good Tanyas.

title: Good News For People Who Love Bad News
summary: Produced by Dennis Herring (Camper Van Beethoven), the latest release from the Seattle-based indie rockers sees a return of guitarist Dann Gallucci (last with the band on Sad Sappy Sucker) and a new drummer (Benjamin Weikel) as well as a guest spot from the Dirty Dozen Brass Band.

title: Once In A Lifetime
summary: This 3-disc attractively-packaged retrospective on the groundbreaking New York band includes completely remastered tracks from each of their studio LPs as well as the same previously-unreleased-on-CD demos and new tracks included on the earlier 2-disc Sand In the Vaseline complilation. Also included are never-before-released alternate versions of five songs. The set also contains a DVD with an updated version of the Talking Heads music video compilation Storytelling Giant, with three additional videos not found on the original VHS release.

title: Red Dirt Road
summary: The duo of Kix Brooks and Ronnie Dunn return with a follow-up to 2001's 'Steers and Stripes.'

title: Me & Giuliani Down By the School Yard (A True Story) [EP]
summary: Search engines hate them, but !!! (pronounced "Chik Chik Chik," of course) are popular with live audiences for their funkier, dancier (yes, that's a word--trust us) approach to indie music. The Sacramento band shares three members with Out Hud, and this is their 2-song debut for Touch And Go (with a full album to follow in 2004).

title: In Search Of... [Second Version]
summary: This is the debut album for in-demand hip-hop production duo The Neptunes, recording with Shay under the name N.E.R.D. (for "No One Ever Really Dies"). Note that there are two different versions of this album in circulation. The original version, featuring mainly electronic instrumentation, was intended for release in August 2001 but was shelved by the band (only to be released in the UK over the band's objection). This new version, released March 2002, was completely rerecorded, and features live instrumentation by Minneapolis funk band Spymob.

title: lilac6
summary: Brothers Nick and Stephen "Tin Tin" Duffy return for the Lilac Time's sixth LP. The Barenaked Ladies' Stephen Page also contributes to the album.

title: All Melody
summary: The ninth full-length studio release for the German electronic composer/producer was recorded in his studio in the East Berlin Funkhaus building.

title: Wounded Rhymes
summary: Sweden's Lykke Li continues to disarm listeners with her distinctive voice on her second album, keeping in tune with her tough sensuality and pop whimsy.

title: Mozart's Mini-Mart
summary: The third full-length release for the indie rock band led by Lawrence (frontman for Felt and Denim) was produced with Papernut Cambridge's Ian Button.

title: Tryptych
summary: Released separately in 2010 as three vinyl records, Forest of Evil, Liberation Through Hearing, and Voices of Dust are released together with additional tracks as a three-CD set for 2011.

title: Fear Fun
summary: J. Tillman, the former drummer for Fleet Foxes releases his debut solo album as Father John Misty.

title: Follow Them True
summary: The second full-length release for the British folk quintet led by singer Nicola Kearey was produced by the band's guitarist Ian Carter.

title: Majesty Shredding
summary: This is the first studio album in nine years for the Chapel Hill, North Carolina, indie rock band Superchunk.

title: And Then Nothing Turned Itself Inside-Out
summary: Aside from the noisy "Cherry Chapstick," the tracks on And Then Nothing showcase a mellower sound for the Hoboken, NJ three-piece, which disappointed some long-time fans but certainly won over critics.

title: Placeholder
summary: The second full-length release for the Meg Duffy project was produced with Brad Cook.

title: Significant Changes
summary: The debut full-length release for the Canadian DJ/producer features a guest appearance from Alexa Dash.

title: Reloaded
summary: The New York rapper produced ten of the 15 tracks on his second full-length solo album that also features production from The Alchemist, The Arch Druids, Q-Tip, and Ray West.

title: L.A Witch
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the Los Angeles trio of Sade Sanchez, Ellie English and Irita Pai.

title: Moodymann
summary: The Detroit techno artist's latest release includes guest appearances from Amp Fiddler, Andres, and José James.

title: Be
summary: The rapper's follow-up to 2002's love-it-or-hate-it 'Electric Circus' was produced largely by Kanye West. For some reason, John Mayer guests.

title: Megafaun
summary: This is the fourth album for the North Carolina rock trio who at one time were in a band with Justin Vernon named DeYarmond Edison.

title: Typical System
summary: This is the second full-length studio release for the Melbourne, Australia-based post-punk band formed by Dan Stewart and Mikey Young.

title: Night Network
summary: The eighth full-length studio release for the British indie rock trio was recorded at the Foo Fighters' Los Angeles studio and was self-produced.

title: Working Men's Club
summary: The debut full-length release for the British band led by Sydney Minsky-Sargeant was produced by Ross Orton.

title: Something About April II
summary: The sequel to 2011's Something About April features guest appearances from Bilal, Karolina, Raphael Saadiq, and Stereolab's Laetitia Sadier.

title: Blaqkout
summary: This is the first album to feature DJ Quik and Kurupt together.

title: Centralia
summary: The sixth release of acoustic instrumentation and electronics for the Brooklyn-based duo was self-recorded, edited, and mixed.

title: Never Will
summary: The second full-length release on Warner Music Nashville for the country artist was produced by Jay Joyce.

title: Brighter Than Creation's Dark
summary: This is the first album since Jason Isbell left the band to pursue a solo career.

title: The Hunter
summary: The Atlanta metal band's first album that is not a concept release was produced by Mike Elizondo.

title: A Winged Victory for the Sullen
artist: A Winged Victory for the Sullen
summary: The duo of Dustin O'Halloran and Stars of the Lid's Adam Wiltzie release their debut album as A Winged Victory for the Sullen.

title: Scandalous
summary: The retro-soul rock quartet, featuring an eight-piece horn section, offers up a funky blend of R&B and blues reminiscent of early J. Geils Band, James Brown, and Otis Redding.

title: Future Me Hates Me
summary: The debut full-length release for the indie pop/rock quartet formed at the University of Auckland was produced by the band's guitarist Jonathan Pearce.

title: Surrounded by Time
summary: The latest full-length covers release from the Welsh artist was co-produced by Ethan Johns and Mark Woodward.

title: Pangs
summary: The second full-length release for the Scottish singer-songwriter was recorded by Julie McLarnon.

title: The Narrows
summary: The eighth solo release for the Nashville-based California singer-songwriter was self-produced and was recorded at Dan Auerbach's Easy Eye Studio.

title: Music in Exile
summary: The debut full-length release for the Malian band was co-produced by Yeah Yeah Yeahs’ Nick Zinner and Marc-Antoine Moreau.

title: Wild Flag
summary: The indie supergroup, featuring Carrie Brownstein and Janet Weiss of Sleater-Kinney, releases its debut power pop album.

title: Blackjazz
summary: The Norwegian band led by Jorgen Munkeby has a sharper metal edge than Jaga Jazzist, which was Munkeby's previous band.

title: Swim
summary: The Canadian electronic artist releases his follow-up to his Polaris Music Prize-winning album Andorra.

title: Harlem River Blues
summary: The third album for the son of Steve Earle was produced with Skylar Wilson.

title: Identity Crisis
summary: Don't be fooled by the title: While 'Identity Crisis' would have perfectly suited her poorly-received predecessor, 2001's Glen Ballard-produced 'Love, Shelby,' that's not the case here, as these 12 self-produced tracks are more likely to connect with fans of her breakthrough disc 'I Am Shelby Lynne.'

title: Shine A Light
summary: The Ontario, Canada band makes its Sub Pop (and U.S.) debut with this, their second LP, which mixes alternative rock with punk and soul.

title: Think Tank
summary: The veteran Britpop outfit's first new album in four years is the result of tumultuous recording sessions in Morocco with producer Fatboy Slim, which saw a growing dispute between co-founders Damon Albarn and Graham Coxon culminate in Coxon's departure from the band. Fatboy Slim only wound up producing two tracks, with William Orbit handling some of the others.

title: Master And Everyone

title: Midnite Vultures
summary: Beck's "official" follow-up to 'Odelay' is an even more eclectic mix of soul, electro, funk, folk, rock, and hip-hop, including more than one song that sounds an awful lot like Prince.

title: Bang Bang Rock & Roll
summary: The London-based art-rockers led by Eddie Argos make their official debut with this 12-song effort.

title: Grinderman
summary: This self-titled disc is the first release for the new project from Nick Cave, who adds "guitar player" to his CV. Seeing as how most of the Bad Seeds join in as well, we're still not sure why the new name was necessary. (Actually, it sounds even more like their earlier band, The Birthday Party.)

title: Love vs Money
summary: The second album for the producer/singer was produced with Chrstopher "Tricky" Stewart and features guest appearances by Kanye West, Mariah Carey, and Lil Jon.

title: Hopelessness
summary: The debut solo release for the lead singer of Antony And The Johnsons was produced by Oneohtrix Point Never and Hudson Mohawke.

title: Choral
summary: The third album for the Brooklyn-based duo who met at the School of the Arts Institute of Chicago.

title: Down Where the Spirit Meets the Bone
summary: Produced with Tom Overby and Greg Leisz, the 11th studio release for singer-songwriter includes a song based on a poem by her father, Miller Williams.

title: Blackbirds
summary: The eighth studio release from the Nashville singer-songwriter was co-produced with Doug Lancio and Barry Walsh.

title: Chatma
summary: The third release for the Malian Tuareg group features former Tinariwen's singer Wonou Walet Sidati.

title: Look Around the Corner
summary: This is the first release of Latin soul with Alice Russell and Quantic.

title: Clockdust
summary: The second full-length solo release for Talk Talk's Paul Webb as Rustin Man contains music from the same sessions as Drift Code.

title: Twenty-Five for the Rest of Our Lives
summary: This is the second full-length album for the Los Angeles rock band led by brothers Andy and Joey Siara.

title: Black Noise
summary: The third album for the German techno artist features Animal Collective's Noah Lennox (aka Panda Bear) and !!!/LCD Soundsystem's Tyler Pope as guest artists.

title: You Could Have It So Much Better
summary: The Scottish band's eagerly-awaited follow-up to their acclaimed self-titled debut is preceded by yet another insanely catchy single, "Do You Want To."

title: The Universe Inside
summary: The latest release for the band led by Steve Wynn features a guest appearance from The Long Ryders' Stephen McCarthy and was recorded in an 80-minute studio session.

title: Under Color of Official Right
summary: The second full-length release for the Detroit post-punk band was recorded in one weekend by Bill Skibbe and Jessica Ruffins.

title: Eyes & Nines
summary: The Bronx's Joby Ford produces the Sacramento-based hard rock band's third full-length album.

title: It Still Moves
summary: The Southern rockers make their major-label debut with this 12-track effort.

title: Electric Messiah
summary: The eighth full-length studio release for the Oakland, California-based metal band led by Matt Pike was produced by Kurt Ballou.

title: SVIIB
summary: Alejandra Deheza and Benjamin Curtis were working on the Brooklyn  band's fourth (and now final) album when Curtis died from lymphoma in December 2013.

title: A Written Testimony
summary: The debut full-length studio release for the rapper features guest appearances from Jay-Z, Travis Scott and The-Dream.

title: The Visiter
summary: The San Francisco, California-based duo releases its sophomore album.

title: You Make Me Feel
summary: The third full-length release for the Memphis R&B/soul singer-songwriter was produced by Scott Bomar.

title: A Bath Full of Ecstasy
summary: The seventh full-length studio release for British indie electronic group features production from Rodaidh McDonald and Philippe Zdar.

title: Miri
summary: The fifth full-length release for the Malian folk band features guest appearances from Majid Bekkas, Afel Bocoum, Abdoulaye Diabate, Casey Driessen, Dom Flemons, Yasel González Rivera, Habib Koite, and Michael League.

title: Street Safari
summary: The second full-length release for the New York post-punk band led by John Eatherly was produced by Patrick Wimberly.

title: Woodland Echoes
summary: The first solo release in nearly 20 years for the British singer-songwriter who was also the frontman for Haircut One Hundred was produced with his son Oliver, Ian Shaw, and Phillip Taylor.

title: Goodnight Rhonda Lee
summary: The fourth full-length release for the singer-songwriter was produced by Nile City Sound and recorded live to tape in five days.

title: Love On The Inside
summary: The third album for the country duo of Jennifer Nettles and Kristian Bush.

title: God's Favorite Customer
summary: The fourth full-length release for Josh Tillman as Father John Misty was written mostly in New York, including a two-months at a hotel and features contributions from Dave Cerminara, Haxan Cloak, Natalie Mering of Weyes Blood, Jonathan Rado, Trevor Spencer, and Jonathan Wilson.

title: For the First Time
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the British septet was recorded live over seven days with producer Andy Savours.

title: We're New Here
summary: Remixed by Jamie XX, R&B and hip hop samples are added to Gil Scott-Heron's 2010 album I'm New Here, creating this latest release.

title: The Boy Named If
summary: The latest full-length release from Elvis Costello And The Imposters features a guest appearance from Nicole Atkins.

title: The Sunset Tree
summary: John Darnielle recorded this 13-track Mountain Goats disc with the help of musicians John Vanderslice, Peter Hughes, Franklin Bruno and Scott Solter.

title: Arpo
summary: The second full-length release for Berlin-based experimental electronic artist Joe Seaton features the clarinet and oboe played by his father, David Seaton.

title: Outer Heaven
summary: The second full-length release for the the Toronto-based rock band led by Shehzaad Jiwani was produced by Mike Rocha.

title: Nikki Nack
summary: The third full-length release for the music project of Merrill Garbus was produced by John Hill and Malay.

title: Nashville
summary: The soul singer tackles 14 country tunes with the help of producer Buddy Miller and guests Emmylou Harris, Gillian Welch, Dolly Parton, Patty Loveless And Patti Griffin.

title: Songs of Praise
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the British post-punk quintet that includes Charlie Steen, Sean Coyle-Smith, Eddie Green, Josh Finerty, and Charlie Forbes.

title: Soused
summary: The second collaboration between Scott Walker and Sunn O))) is a five-track album produced by Scott Walker and Peter Walsh.

title: Idiology
summary: The German electro-experimenters return with a follow up to last year's 'Niun Niggung.'

title: High
summary: The second and final full-length release for the Australian garage punk band with its lead singer Shogun, who left the band in 2014, but agreed to finish this sophomore album.

title: Age Of
summary: The ninth full-length release for producer Daniel Lopatin features contributions from Anohni, James Blake, Eli Keszler, Kelsey Lu, and Prurient.

title: A  Brief Inquiry into Online Relationships
summary: The third full-length release for the British rock band was produced by the band's own Matthew Healy and George Daniel.

title: Four the Record
summary: The aptly titled fourth album for the country singer features a duet with her husband, Blake Shelton.

title: Abysskiss
summary: The latest full-length solo release for the Big Thief frontwoman was produced by Luke Temple.

title: PUP
summary: The debut full-length release for the Toronto punk band that originally was named Topanga (a reference to the Boy Meets World character).

title: Carboniferous
summary: The Italian trio that mixes metal, jazz, and punk influences in its music releases its first album on the Ipecac label.

title: Forevher
summary: The second full-length release for the British pop artist was inspired by her own long-distance relationship.

title: Loom
summary: The debut full-length studio release for the British indie pop trio of Jessica Weiss, Daniel Falvey (Guitar), and Michael Miles is a follow-up to its 2012 single compilation, "Early Fragments."

title: The Long Goodbye
summary: The first full-length release not credited under the actor/rapper's MC name was produced by Swet Shop Boys' Redinho.

title: New Hymn to Freedom
summary: The second full-length release for the British trio that includes producer Luke Abbott, Triosk/PVT's Laurence Pike and Portico Quartet's Jack Wyllie was improvised and recorded live.

title: We Are King
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the electro-soul trio of Anita Bias, and sisters Paris and Amber Strother.

title: Futurology
summary: The 12th full-length release for the Welsh alternative rock trio was recorded at the same time as 2013's Rewind the Film and features guest appearances from Cian Ciaran, Green Gartside, Nina Hoss, and  Georgia Ruth.

title: What a Time to Be Alive
summary: The 11th full-length studio release for the indie rock band led by Mac McCaughan features guest appearances from David Bazan, Katie Crutchfield, Sabrina Ellis, Skylar Gudasz, and Stephin Merritt.

title: Seek Shelter
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the Danish post-punk band was produced with Nis Bysted and Sonic Boom.

title: Spare Ribs
summary: The 11th full-length studio release for the British punk duo features Billy Nomates and Amyl and The Sniffers' Amy Taylor.

title: Clarity
summary: The debut full-length release for the German pop artist was produced by Dr. Luke, Aaron Joseph and Brandon Hamlin.

title: Party
summary: The second full-length release for the New Zealand singer-songwriter was produced by John Parish.

title: M
summary: The debut full-length black metal solo release for Ex Cops' Amalie Bruun was produced by Kristoffer Rygg.

title: Mr Twin Sister
summary: The second full-length release for the New York indie pop band previously known as Twin Sister was produced by Jonathan Low.

title: Angels of Darkness, Demons of Light, Vol. 2
summary: The second volume in the Angels of Darkness, Demons of Light series from the Seattle-based quartet led by Dylan Carlson comprises five songs.

title: Lianne La Havas
summary: The third full-length release for the British singer-songwriter was produced with Matt Hales, Beni Giles, and Mura Masa.

title: Circumambulation
summary: The third full-length release for the Texas self-described-"stone gaze" trio was produced by Matt Pence and is its first on the Relapse label.

title: Love Behind The Melody
summary: The sophomore album already has one Grammy-nominated single, "Woman."

title: For Their Love
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Oklahoma indie rock band was recorded in Oregon and was self-produced.

title: Blue Sky Noise
summary: The rock quintet moves to Atlantic Records for its third album, which was produced by David Bottrill.

title: All That Reckoning
summary: The first full-length studio release in six years for the Canadian alt-country/folk rock band led by Michael Timmins.

title: Luck In The Valley
summary: The final album for the Pelt member, who passed away in December 2009, contains 10 instrumental tracks.

title: Star Wars
summary: Produced by Jeff Tweedy and Tom Schick, the ninth release was a surprise free release on the Chicago band's website for a limited time.

title: Safe
summary: This is the debut full-length release for grime producer Louis Carnell.

title: Music Tapes for Clouds & Tornadoes

title: Stubborn Persistent Illusions

title: Homesongs

title: Morph The Cat
summary: This is the Steely Dan vocalist's first solo disc in over a dozen years.

title: Field Songs
summary: The Iowa songwriter releases a full-length album of alt-rock, blues, and folk.

title: Primrose Green
summary: This is the second full-length release for the Chicago singer-songwriter.
This Alan Moulder-produced disc from the Kazu Makino-fronted band follows three years after 'Misery Is A Butterfly.'

title: Collapsed in Sunbeams
summary: The debut full-length release for the British singer-songwriter was produced by Gianluca Buccellati.

title: Likewise
summary: The debut full-length solo release for the Hop Along singer was recorded with her Hop Along bandmate, Joe Reinhart.

title: Drone Logic
summary: The debut full-length release for the British techno producer includes influences from acid house, drone, IDM, and shoegaze music.

title: Hubris
summary: The latest release from the Australian composer features guest appearances from such artists as Mark Fell, Jim O'Rourke, and Ricardo Villalobos.

title: Drift
summary: This is the debut full-length album for the Los Angeles producer/DJ.

title: If You See Me, Say Yes

title: Whole & Cloven

title: Andorra

title: Royal Toast

title: A Boot And A Shoe

title: B'lieve I'm Goin' Down

title: Boy

title: Midnight Manor
summary: The second full-length release for the North Carolina rock sextet was produced by Oakley Munson of the Black Lips.

title: The Whole Love
summary: The Chicago alternative rock band releases its eighth studio album on its own label dBom.

title: Blood Mountain
summary: The Atlanta metal band's third album marks their major-label debut.

summary: The New York electronic producer worked with Patrick Higgins on his latest full-length release under his own name.

The very, very distinctive Icelandic band generated an enormous amount of positive press (and deservingly so) for their previous effort, 'Ágætis Byrjun,' which led to a major-label deal and this album, which, like each of its eight tracks, does not have a real title.

title: Option Paralysis

summary: The third full-length release for the singer-songwriter was recorded with Peter Broderick and Alasdair Roberts.

title: Major/Minor
summary: The Southern California rock band releases their seventh album of melodic alternative rock.

title: (a)spera

title: Pang

title: Daniel Bachman
summary: The seventh full-length solo studio release for the guitarist was recorded by Brian Haran.

title: When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?

title: Epic

Stetson employed circular breathing and used approximately two dozen microphones, placing them on the studio walls, throughout his bass saxophone, and on his throat to produce this otherworldly-sounding album.

title: Weird Little Birthday

title: Sepalcure

title: Stonechild

title: Our Shadows Will Remain

title: Southern Blood
summary: The final release for the singer-songwriter who passed away in May 2017 was produced by Don Was.

title: Luminiferous

title: Nothing Violates This Nature

summary: This is the second release for former Jackie-O Motherfucker member Natalie Mering as Weyes Blood.

title: Dark Matter

title: Shackles Gift
summary: The second full-length release for the Bristol-based rock band was produced by Andrew Hung of Fuck Buttons.

title: The Outsiders
summary: The fourth full-length studio release for the country rock artist was produced by Jay Joyce.

title: Nothing Great About Britain
summary: The debut full-length release for the British grime rapper features guest appearances from Jaykae, Mura Masa and Skepta.

title: Polymer

title: Heaven

title: Woman King [EP]

title: At Weddings

title: Stranger in the Alps
summary: The debut full-length release for the Los Angeles-based indie folk singer-songwriter was produced by Tony Berg and Ethan Grusk.

title: The  Assassination of Julius Caesar

title: The Waiting Room
summary: The 10th full-length studio release for the British indie rock band features guest appearances from Jehnny Beth of Savages and Lhasa De Sel.

title: Les Voyages de l'ame

summary: The second full-length release for the British singer-songwriter was produced by Dan Auerbach

summary: The second full-length studio release for the Nashville-based country artist features a guest appearance from Willie Nelson.

summary: Nino Rojo, the eccentric singer-songwriter's second release of 2004, was recorded during the same sessions that produced 'Rejoicing In The Hands.'

title: Stephen Malkmus
summary: The debut solo release from the former leader of indie-rock legends Pavement.

title: Mad for Sadness
summary: This live recording features 10 tracks, mainly consisting of material from the band's first two albums.

title: Angels of Darkness, Demons of Light, Vol. 1
summary: The pioneers of drone doom return with part one of its latest concept album (Volume 2 is scheduled for 2012).

title: Jaguar
summary: The debut full-length release for the R&B singer-songwriter features contributions from Khalid and SG Lewis.

summary: When the comic supergroup's 2001 debut sold an astounding 6 million copies worldwide, a sequel became necessary. Hence 'Demon Days.' Returning leader Damon Albarn (Blur) and new producer Danger Mouse are joined by guests Shaun Ryder (Happy Mondays), Ike Turner, MF Doom, De La Soul and Dennis Hopper.

title: Football Money
summary: The debut full-length release for the Canadian indie rock band was produced by Aaron Goldstein and mixed by Holy Fuck's Graham Walsh.

title: Sun Racket
summary: This is the first full-length studio release in seven years for the Boston alternative rock trio of Kristin Hersh, David Narcizo and Bernard Georges.

title: Towards Language

title: We are Beautiful, We Are Doomed

title: Burning the Threshold

title: Animal

title: Construction Time & Demolition

title: Back to Love
summary: The fourth release for the soul singer features production from Babyface, James Poyser, Kelvin Wooten, and Salaam Remi.

title: Now Only

title: Oh No
summary: The second full-length release for the Canadian electronic artist was produced with Junior Boys' Jeremy Greenspan.

title: Floating Coffin
summary: The latest release from the San Francisco rock band led by John Dwyer is its first on the Castle Face label.

Guests include Dave Longstreth (Dirty Projectors), Steve Lacy (The Internet), Danielle Haim, and Jenny Lewis.

title: Alphabetland

title: The Future and the Past

title: Little Seeds

title: Furnaces

title: Bears, Mayors, Scraps & Bones
summary: This is the third full-length album for the Canadian punk rock band.

title: Overgrown

title: We Shall Overcome: The Seeger Sessions

summary: The latest full-length solo studio release for the Los Angeles-based singer-songwriter was written while staying in Wales.

summary: The Norwegian producer's album has only three tracks, but one is nearly 29 minutes long.

title: Lowedges

title: What We Say in Private

summary: The debut full-length release for the duet between Vijay Iyer and Wadada Leo Smith was produced by Manfred Eicher.

summary: The second album under his real name combines the sounds of electronic, folk and rock music.

The British folk singer-songwriter worked with Steve Gunn, who also produced the album features guest vocals from Bridget St John and a band that includes Nathan Bowles, James Elkington, and Jimy SeiTang.

Multi-instrumentalist Jim O'Rourke, who worked with the band on their previous effort 'NYC Ghosts & Flowers,' is now a full-fledged member of the group.

summary: Often compared to Doves and Radiohead, Manchester-based Elbow is yet another new alternative band to emerge from the British music press hype machine. This debut album was shortlisted for 2001's Mercury Music Prize.

title: Discovery of a World Inside the Moone
All the Time
summary: The third full-length release for the New York-based Canadian pop artist was again produced with Junior Boys' Jeremy Greenspan.

title: Matador

The Final Report contains songs by Chris Carter, Peter Christopherson, and Cosey Fanni Tutti before Christopherson passed away in 2010.

artist: The Ghost of a Saber Tooth Tiger

summary: The latest full-length solo release for the singer-songwriter features guest appearances from Chris Cohen, Carolyn Pennypacker-Riggs and Joan Shelley.

title: Saturation III

title: Beware of the Dogs

title: Shape & Destroy
summary:
The second full-length release for the Nashville-based singer-songwriter 
was produced with Jarrad Kritzstein.

title: Memory

summary: The second full-length release for the New York City alternative rock/pop band was produced by Joe Chiccarelli.

Former producer (and former husband) Mitchell Froom is gone, replaced by Rupert Hine, who creates an overall sound that is more like Vega's earliest recordings than her Froom-produced output during the 1990s.

title: Ivy Tripp

title: Atlanta Millionaires Club

title: Tears Of The Valedictorian

summary: The posthumous release for the Ohio singer-songwriter was recorded in 2008.

title: The Unraveling
summary: The 12th full-length studio release for the alt-country/southern rock band was recorded in Memphis with Matt Ross-Spang and producer David Barbe.

title: Lush
summary: The debut full-length release for 18-year-old British indie rock singer-songwriter Lindsey Jordan was produced by Jake Aron.

title: The Disco's of Imhotep
summary: This is the debut full-length solo studio release for Chicago house producer Jamal Moss.

title: When the Cellar Children See the Light of Day
summary: The second release for the Finnish singer-songwriter was produced by Vladislav Delay.

title: Cruise Your Illusion
summary: The debut full-length release for the Olympia, Washington indie punk quartet formed by brothers, Alex Coxen and Joe Rutter.

title: Endless Falls
summary: The latest ambient album for Scott Morgan, the Canadian producer, features a spoken word track with Destroyer's Dan Bejar.

title: The Slow Wonder
summary: This is the first solo release for Carl Newman, who can also be found leading indie-rock supergroup The New Pornographers as well as the (now defunct) Canadian power-pop band Zumpano.

title: Hate
summary: The Glasgow, Scotland-based band follow 2000's stunning 'The Great Eastern' with this, their fourth (and almost equally stunning) LP.  Dave Fridmann (Mercury Rev) returns as producer.

title: Yanqui U.X.O.
summary: Slightly (and confusingly) changing their name to Godspeed You! Black Emperor for this outing, the Canadian instrumental band recorded these 5 tracks (clocking in at 75 minutes) with Steve Albini as a follow-up to their extremely well-received 2000 effort 'Lift Yr Skinny Fists Like Antennas To Heaven.'

title: Pajo
summary: This is Slint guitarist David Pajo's first solo LP under his own name (well, at least half of his own name).

title: The Bones of What You Believe
summary: This is the debut full-length studio release for the Scottish synth-pop trio.

title: The Besnard Lakes Are The Roaring Night
summary: The indie rock quartet led by music producer Jace Lasek and his wife Olga releases its second album on the Jagjaguwar label.

title: Super Taranta!
summary: The second album from Side One Dummy Records for the New York band who are influenced by gypsy music.

title: The Libertines
summary: While some eponymous albums suggest a lack of creativity, the heralded UK rock outfit's sophomore disc is titled 'The Libertines' because it is indeed about The Libertines--or, more specifically, about the ongoing conflict between the band's two songwriters, Carlos Barat and Pete Doherty (the latter of whom was subsequently kicked out of the band after three failed rehab attempts). The Clash's Mick Jones returns as producer.

title: Atlas Vending
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Toronto punk rock trio was co-produced with Uniform's Ben Greenberg.

title: The Sun's Tirade
summary: The debut full-length studio release for the Tennessee rap artist features guest appearances from Deacon Blues, Kari Faux, Hugh Augustine, Kendrick Lamar, Jay Rock, SiR, Syd the Kid, SZA, and Zacari.

title: Twelfth
summary: The 12th full-length studio release for the alt-country band was recorded in Nashville and was produced by Vance Powell.

title: Compliments Please
summary: The debut full-length release for the solo project from former Slow Club member Rebecca Taylor was produced by The Very Best's Johan Karlberg.

title: Fixed Ideals
summary: The second full-length release for the British pop-punk trio led by Lande Hekt was produced and mixed by Lewis Johns.

title: Good Time [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]
summary: The soundtrack by Daniel Lopatin for the 2017 film directed by Josh and Benny Safdie was awarded the Best Soundtrack Award at Cannes.

title: Gulag Orkestar
summary: This Eastern European-sounding, multi-instrumental effort is actually the work of Albuquerque teenager Zach Condon. Members of A Hawk And A Hacksaw also lend a hand.

title: BE
summary: The latest full-length studio release for the South Korean pop band features production from Brasstracks and Cosmo's Midnight.

title: The Way The Wind Blows
summary: This is the third Hawk album for former Neutral Milk Hotel drummer Jeremy Barnes. Like previous efforts, it has an Eastern European flavor, although unlike previous efforts, it also includes contributions from Beirut's Zach Condon.

title: Nootropics
summary: The second album for the Baltimore-based indie rock band led by Jana Hunter was produced Drew Brown.

title: My Krazy Life
summary: The debut full-length studio release for the Los Angeles rapper features guest appearances from Drake, Jeezy, Kendrick Lamar, Jay Rock, Schoolboy Q, and Ty Dolla $ign.

title: Everything is Love
summary: The debut full-length collaborative album for Beyonce and Jay-Z was a surprise release and features guest appearances from Migos, Offset, Quavo, Rory from Stone Love, and Ty Dolla $ign.

title: 3001: A Laced Odyssey
summary: The debut full-length studio release for the Brooklyn-based rap trio of Meechy Darko, Zombie Juice and Erick “The Architect” Elliott features guest appearances from Diamante and Anthony Flammia.

title: 13 & God
summary: 13+God is a collaboration between German rocktronica outfit The Notwist and American indie-rappers Themselves. Also guesting are members of Ms. John Soda, Lali Puna, and cLOUDDEAD; basically, if they're on Morr Music or Anticon, you'll find them here.

title: Are You Alone?
summary: The second full-length release for Canadian duo Devon Welsh and Matthew Otto features contributions from Owen Pallett.

title: Assume Form
summary: The fourth full-length release for the British electronic producer features guest appearances from André 3000, Metro Boomin, Rosalía, Travis Scott, and Moses Sumney.

title: All My Demons Greeting Me as a Friend
summary: The Norwegian dark pop singer-songwriter worked with Odd Martin Skalnes and Magnus Skylstad on her debut full-length release.

title: Be Small
summary: The fourth release for the quintet-turned duo of Luke Temple and Michael Bloch was self-produced.

title: Throw It to the Universe
summary: The sixth release for the Swedish rock band is said to be its final album.

title: Side Effects
summary: The ninth full-length studio release for the Austin rock band features some songs that were either demos, outtakes or were not included in previous albums.

title: Desperate Man
summary: The sixth full-length studio release for the Nashville-based country artist was produced by Jay Joyce.

title: Fresh Blood
summary: The second full-length release from the indie rock artist was produced with Trey Pollard.

title: Tetsuo & Youth
summary: The fifth studio release for the rapper features guest appearances from  Ab-Soul and Nikki Jean.

title: The Eldritch Dark
summary: The third full-length release for the Canadian doom metal band was produced by Ian Blurton.

title: We The Vehicles
summary: This second Maritime LP is the final one to feature former Dismemberment Plan bassist Eric Axelson, who left the group (which also includes former members of the Promise Ring) after its recording.

title: Django Django
summary: This is the debut release for the indie London-based quartet that began at an Edinburgh art school.

title: Besnard Lakes Are the Last of the Great Thunderstorm Warnings
summary: The latest full-length release for the Canadian psych-rock group was produced by the band's own Jace Lasek and Olga Goreas.

title: The Con
summary: The Canadian twins' latest album features members of Death Cab for Cutie and AFI.

title: Nature Always Wins
summary: The seventh full-length studio release for the British rock band was produced by Ben Allen and features a guest appearance from Pauline Murray.

title: Performance
summary: The eighth full-length studio release for the Texas rock band was recorded in Austin over eight weeks.

title: Lifeforms
summary: The sixth full-length studio release for the alternative rock band led by Tom DeLonge is its first on the Rise label.

title: Black Age Blues
summary: The first release in over 11 years for the doom band was produced by Nick Raskulinecz.

title: I Like to Keep Myself in Pain
summary: The first solo album in over 11 years for the Georgia singer includes songs written for her by Andrew Bird, Vic Chesnutt, John Wesley Harding, Robyn Hitchcock, the Mekons' Jon Langford, Stephin Merritt, and M. Ward.

title: Losing Feeling [EP]
summary: This is the latest four-track EP for the Los Angeles-based indie rock duo.

title: Feathers
summary: This self-titled disc marks the debut for the Vermont freak-folk outfit.

title: Farmer's Corner
summary: The latest release from James Jackson Toth as Wooden Wand was recorded over six different sessions.

title: Citrus
summary: Their music sounds British and the vocals are sometimes in Japanese, but this four-piece shoegaze outfit (returning here with a second album) hails from Brooklyn.

title: Manic
summary: The third full-length release for the alternative pop artist features guest appearances Dominic Fike, Alanis Morissette and BTS' Suga.

title: I, I
summary: The fourth full-length release for the indie folk band led by Justin Vernon features contributions from such artists as James, Blake, the Brooklyn Youth Chorus, BJ Burton, S. Carey, Aaron & Bryce Dessner, Phil Cook, Moses Sumney and Bruce Hornsby, and Wye Oak's Jenn Wasner.

title: Abandon All Life
summary: The second full-length release for the Southern California metal band was produced by Converge guitarist, Kurt Ballou.

title: The Black Swan
summary: The veteran British folkie is joined by Espers, Devendra Banhart and Beth Orton on his latest release.

title: Awfully Deep
summary: This is the third album for London-based rapper Rodney Smith.

title: Anna Calvi
summary: The half-English, half-Italian singer's self-titled debut showcases her sophisticated songwriting abilities -- drawing comparisons to PJ Harvey -- and her musical prowess.

title: All a Man Should Do
summary: The 11th full-length studio release from the Memphis alt-country punk rock band was produced by Ted Hutt.

title: Distant Satellites
summary: The tenth full-length studio release for the British rock band was produced by Christer-André Cederberg.

title: Here's My Song You Can Have It... I Don't Want It Anymore/Yours 4-Ever
summary: The Swedish singer-songwriter and former soccer player is backed by Mercury Rev on his latest release (which originally emerged in 2004 in Europe).

title: Electric Brick Wall
summary: This is the second release for the alternative rock band led by former Royal Trux member Jennifer Herrema.

title: Vivian Girls
summary: The debut album for the Brooklyn trio is less than 22 minutes long.

title: Pawn Shoppe Heart
summary: The Detroit garage rockers make their major-label debut with this sophomore album, which was produced by Jerry Harrison.

title: American III: Solitary Man
summary: In his sixth decade of recording, Johnny Cash reunites with producer Rick Rubin for a third consecutive outing. Like its two predecessors, 'III' consists of a mix of Cash originals and covers, this time from the likes of Nick Cave ("The Mercy Seat"), Tom Petty ("I Won't Back Down"), and U2 ("One").

title: Thirteen Tales From Urban Bohemia
summary: The third album from the Portland, Ore. indie-rock band failed to elevate their standing in their home country, although they continue to sell well (and receive favorable press) in Europe.

title: All Of A Sudden I Miss Everyone
summary: The instrumental post-rock band from Texas returns after a four-year wait with this fourth studio album.

title: Give the People What They Want
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the Brooklyn soul band was originally scheduled for an August release but was delayed due to the cancer diagnosis of singer Sharon Jones.

title: Denies The Day's Demise
summary: The Los Angeles-based electronica artist's fifth album has a bit of a Brazilian feel.

title: Corsicana Lemonade
summary: Produced by Jim Vollentine, The sixth full-length studio release for the Austin band includes two tracks produced by Wilco's Jeff Tweedy.

title: 12 Bit Blues
summary: Samples from early blues records are used in the sixth studio album for the Canadian DJ.

title: DS2
summary: The third full-length studio release for the Atlanta rapper was named after his 2011 mixtape Dirty Sprite and features a guest appearance from Drake.

title: Fall Heads Roll
summary: Mark E. Smith & Co. return with their full-length follow-up to 'The Real New Fall LP.'

title: Ya-Ka-May
summary: Heavily influenced by hip-hop, rock, blues, funk, and jazz, the New Orleans "Bounce" quintet Galactic enlists vocal legends for its sixth studio effort. These include Rebirth Brass Band and Irma Thomas, as well as such up-and-coming Bounce artists as Cheeky Blakk, Big Freedia, and Sissy Nobby.

title: The Angels Of Light Sing 'Other People'
summary: Michael Gira's post-Swans project Angels Of Light returns with a fourth release of mostly acoustic folk/rock, backed by musicians from Akron/Family.

title: Animated Violence Mild
summary: This is the fourth full-length studio release for the electronic solo project of Fuck Buttons' Benjamin John Power.

title: Small Town Heroes
summary: The latest release for the folk ensemble led by Alynda Lee Segarra is its first on the ATO label.

title: Exai
summary: The 11th full-length release from the British electronic duo of Sean Booth and Rob Brown is over two hours long.

title: Private Space
summary: The third full-length studio release for the Indiana retro-soul group features synths and disco influences.

title: The Last Exit
summary: This is the fifth full-length release for the duo of Tessa Murray and Greg Hughes.

title: Powers
summary: The first full-length release in seven years for the British post-punk band was self-produced.

title: Horizon
summary: The third full-length release for the British post-punk trio is its first in five years.

title: Black Friday
summary: The third full-length release for the Boston-based indie rock trio led by Ellen Kempner was co-produced with Gabe Wax.

title: A Laughing Death in Meatspace
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the Australian rock band that includes The Drones' Gareth Libbiard and Fiona Kitschin; High Tension's Lauren Hammel; and Harmony/Palm Springs' Erica Dunn.

title: Infinite Moment
summary: This is the sixth full-length release for Swedish electronic producer Axel Willner as The Field.

title: Bad Contestant
summary: The debut full-length release for the British singer-songwriter was recorded in 12 days with Alex Burey and Foxygen's Jonathan Rado.

title: Goat Girl
summary: The debut full-length release for British rock band was produced by Dan Carey.

title: Three/Three
summary: The third and final part of Tadd Mullinix's trilogy features guest appearances from Danny Brown, Clear Soul Forces, Denmark Vessey, Doom, Fatt Father, G & D, Guilty Simpson, Ghostface Killah, Silas Green, Intricate Dialect, Kadance, La Peace, Roc Marciano, Georgia Anne Muldrow, Nolan The Ninja, Dudley Perkins, Phat Kat, Quelle Chris, Shigeto, and Jon Wayne.

title: Life Is Fine
summary: The 23rd full-length release for the Australian singer-songwriter features guest appearance from Linda and Vika Bull.

title: Poor David's Almanack
summary: The third release (and the first under just his name) for the guitarist/producer features Gillian Welch as well as Brittany Haas, Paul Kowert, Ketch Secor, and Willie Watson.

title: Also Sprach Zarathustra
summary: The ninth full-length studio release for the Slovenian avant-garde group was originally made for a theatrical production of Thus Spoke Zarathustra (Also Sprach Zarathustra) for the Anton Podbevšek Theatre (APT) in Slovenia.

title: Snake Pit
summary: The latest solo studio release for the blues-rock guitarist who played with such artists as Canned Heat, John Mayall, and the Rolling Stones, was recorded in two days.

title: Fingers Crossed
summary: The latest release for the British rock singer-songwriter was co-produced with Andy York and features Dandy, a tribute to David Bowie.

title: Jura
summary: Originally released on Black Friday Record Store Day in 2015, the Mekons and Robbie Fulks went to the Scottish island of Jura to record the album of acoustic folk songs.

title: Georgia
summary: The full-length debut for the British artist who worked with Kwes and Kate Tempest was self-produced.

title: Give Up Your Dreams
summary: This is the sixth full-length studio release for the New Zealand six-piece band.

title: Worthy
summary: Produced by Joe Henry, the latest release for the soul singer includes songs by the Beatles, Beth Nielsen Chapman, Bob Dylan, Mary Gauthier, and the Rolling Stones.

title: Three Chords Good
summary: Graham Parker reunites with his British rock band, The Rumour, after more than 30 years for this 12-track album produced with Dave Cook.

title: Where Do You Start
summary: Brad Mehldau's second album in 2012 with his jazz trio is a covers album of songs by such artists as Sufjan Stevens, Alice in Chains, Elvis Costello, Nick Drake, and Jimi Hendrix.

title: Quakers
summary: Portishead's Geoff Barrow (under the name Fuzzface), 7-Stu-7 (Portishead's studio engineer, Stuart Matthews), and Katalyst produced the hip-hop album featuring 35 rappers contributing rhymes to the 41-track release.

title: Mariachi El Bronx (II)
summary: This is the second album of mariachi music for El Bronx's alter ego band.

title: In Trance
summary: The third teaming up of British guitarist Justin Adam and Gambian singer Juldeh Camara now includes Billy Fuller on bass and Dave Smith on drums.

title: Gob
summary: The debut LP for the British rapper features production from Micachu, Hot Chip's Joe Goddard, Kwes and Roots Manuva.

title: Regifted Light
summary: The Cleveland-born transgender singer-songwriter's latest album was produced by Andrew W.K.

title: Progress
summary: The British boyband welcomes Robbie Williams back to the group on its sixth album.

title: Ole! Tarantula
summary: The veteran musician is backed by REM and/or Minus 5 members Peter Buck, Scott McCaughey, and Bill Rieflin (together, the Venus 3) on his first release since 2004's 'Spooked.'

title: The Magic Numbers
summary: This debut disc showcases the 50s and 60s pop stylings and three-part harmonies of the pair of brother-sister duos (Romeo & Michelle Stodart and Sean & Angela Gannon) that make up The Magic Numbers.

title: Infiniheart
summary: The Canadian illustrator and musician makes his Sub Pop debut with this self-recorded album.

title: Silver Age
summary: The latest solo studio album for the former Hüsker Dü and Sugar singer is his first on the Merge label.

title: Keepsake
summary: The debut full-length release for the Australian dream pop artist Harriette Pilbeam was produced by John Castle.

title: A Place To Bury Strangers
summary: The debut album for the trio from New York.

title: Still Trippin'
summary: The debut full-length release for the Los Angeles-based footwork producer features guest appearances from DJ Lucky, DJ Manny, DJ Paypal, Chuck Inglish, Odile Myrtil, Fabi Reyna, and UNIIQU3.

title: Sweep It Into Space
summary: The 12th full-length release for the Massachusetts rock trio was produced with Kurt Vile.

title: Oneiric Formulary
summary: The first full-length solo release for the Sun City Girls guitarist in five years.

title: The Take Off and Landing of Everything
summary: The sixth full-length release for the British alternative rock band was again produced by Craig Potter.

title: Pretty Years
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Staten Island rock band led by Joseph D'Agostino was produced by John Congleton.

title: Going Down in History
summary: The first studio release of original songs since 2005's Freedom And Weep from the Chicago alt-country band led by Jon Langford was produced by Mike Hagler.

title: Aquarius
summary: The debut full-length studio release for the R&B singer features guest appearances from A$AP Rocky, Future, Devonté Hynes, and ScHoolboy Q.

title: Tournament Of Hearts
summary: The Canadian rockers follow 'Shine A Light' with this 10-track set.

title: Charli
summary: The third full-length studio release for the British pop artist was produced by A.G. Cook and features guest appearances from Big Freedia, Brooke Candy, Christine and the Queen, Clairo, CupcakKe, Haim, Lizzo, Kim PetrasTroye Sivan, Sky Ferreira, Tommy Cash, Pabllo Vittar, and Yaeji.

title: Night Thoughts
summary: The seventh full-length release for the British alternative rock band was produced by Ed Buller.

title: Hot Dreams
summary: The fifth full-length release for the Canadian folk band led by Taylor Kirk and was produced by Simon Trottier.

title: If I Can't Have Love, I Want Power
summary: Produced by Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross, the fourth full-length studio release for the alternative pop artist is a concept album about pregnancy and giving birth.

title: Pang!
summary: The sixth full-length solo release for the Super Furry Animals frontman was produced and mixed by Muzi.

title: Club Meds
summary: Canadian singer-songwriter Dan Mangan returns as Dan Mangan + Blacksmith for his fourth overall full-length album and it was produced by Colin Stewart.

title: Under The Skin
summary: The Fleetwood Mac guitarist's first solo outing in over a dozen years features bandmates Mick Fleetwood and John McVie on two tracks of a largely acoustic set.

title: Still Life
summary: The second solo full-length release for the Babies/Woods member was inspired by his move from New York to California.

title: Pale Young Gentlemen
summary: The quintet from Madison, Wisconsin self-releases their debut album.

title: The Good Fight
summary: The soul-influenced release for the Brooklyn-based rapper-producer features guest appearances from Gary Clark, Jr., Nick Hakim, Tranqill, and Maimouna Youssef.

title: Give a Glimpse of What Yer Not
summary: The 11th full-length release for the rock trio features nine songs written by J. Mascis and two by Lou Barlow.

title: Boys Outside
summary: The Beta Band's Steve Mason releases his first solo album under his name.

title: Quietly Blowing It
summary: The latest full-length release for the MC Taylor indie folk project features contributions from Griffin and Taylor Goldsmith of Dawes, Josh Kaufman of Bonny Light Horseman, Buddy Miller, and Zach Williams of The Lone Bellow.

title: Carnival of Souls
summary: This is the 15th studio release from the experimental Ohio rock band led by David Thomas.

title: Retrash
summary: The is the debut full-length release for the Chicago trash metal trio.

title: {Awayland}
summary: The second full-length release from the Irishman Conor J. O'Brien was self-produced and includes his touring band: James Byrne, Cormac Curran, Tommy McLaughlin, and Danny Snow.

title: Dive
summary: This is the second album for San Francisco-based graphic design/electronic artist Scott Hansen as Tycho.

title: EP
summary: The Gossip singer releases her solo EP produced by Simian Mobile Disco.

title: Monsters Of Folk
summary: This is the debut album for the band formed by Conor Oberst, Jim James, Mike Mogis, and M. Ward.

title: Songs For Christmas
summary: This five-EP box set collects holiday-themed lo-fi and impromptu tracks (a mix of standards and originals originally intended as gifts for his friends and family) recorded by Stevens over the past five years.

title: The Grind Date
summary: The group's first release on its own AOI label features guests such as Ghostface, MF Doom, Sean Paul, Common and that noted MC Spike Lee. Production assistance comes from Madlib and 9th Wonder.

title: Miss Machine
summary: The inventive but challenging hardcore outfit returns with their first full-length studio recording since 1999's 'Calculating Infinity.'

title: Wig In A Box: Songs From & Inspired By Hedwig & The Angry Inch
summary: Exactly what the title says it is, this 16-track disc features songs from the Hedwig soundtrack (as well as new compositions inspired by the musical) interpreted by your favorite indie artists, including Yo La Tengo (with Yoko Ono!), Spoon, Robyn Hitchcock, The Polyphonic Spree, Frank Black, The Breeders, Bob Mould, and more.

title: O
summary: This full-length debut for the Irish singer/songwriter has moved beyond his home country (where it was a massive hit) to attract critical praise and strong sales worldwide. Mostly self-produced and recorded, the disc also comes in specially-designed packaging including text, artwork and photographs.

title: Monday At The Hug & Pint
summary: The dour Glasgow-based duo of Aidan Moffat and Malcom Middleton return for their fifth studio album, with guest contributions from members of Bright Eyes and Mogwai.

title: Electric Circus
summary: On his fifth album, the underground rapper ventures more into the rock, soul, and jazz territory of his influences, with production help from the Soulaquarians. An eclectic array of guests includes Prince, Erykah Badu, Jill Scott, Bilal, Mary J. Blige, and Stereolab's Laetitia Sadier.

title: C'est La Vie
summary: The seventh full-length studio release for the Alabama-born singer-songwriter was recorded in Nashville and self-produced.

title: I'll Be Lightning
summary: The debut album for the son of Crowded House's Neil Finn.

title: Fading Lines
summary: The debut full-length release for the Dutch indie-pop singer was produced by Ben Greenberg.

title: Yes Lawd!
summary: The debut full-length release for the collaboration between Anderson .Paak and Knxwledge features two tracks from their 2015 EP.

title: The Center Won't Hold
summary: The ninth full-length studio release for the rock trio was produced by St. Vincent and is the final one with drummer Janet Weiss, who announced her departure from the band in July 2019.

title: Pale Horses
summary: The sixth full-length release for the Philadelphia indie rock band was produced by Will Yip.

title: Cascade
summary: The latest release from the ambient artist is a 40-minute piano tape loop.

title: Leave Home
summary: The Brooklyn four-piece (not to be confused with MEN, the JD Samson-led band) releases its third album on new label Sacred Bones.

title: Heaven
summary: The seventh album for indie rock band was produced by Phil Ek.

title: Album
summary: This is the debut album for the San Francisco-based duo of Christopher Owens and Chet White.

title: Exile in the Outer Ring
summary: The third full-length solo release for Erika Anderson was co-produced with Unknown Mortal Orchestra's Jacob Portrait.

title: Run Fast
summary: The debut release for Bikini Kill founder Kathleen Hanna's Julie Ruin project includes Carmine Covelli, Sara Landeau, Kenny Mellman of Kiki And Herb, and Kathi Wilcox of Bikini Kill.

title: The King of Limbs
summary: Released a day earlier than expected as a digital download on February 18th, this is the eighth album from the epic, experimental UK five-piece.

title: Now Here Is Nowhere
summary: This is the full-length debut for the Dallas, TX trio of brothers Benjamin and Brandon Curtis and Josh Garza.

title: The Highwomen
summary: The debut full-length release for the country supergroup that includes Brandi Carlile, Natalie Hemby, Maren Morris, and Amanda Shires was produced by Dave Cobb.

title: Fabriclive 93
summary: Dan Snaith brings 23 new tracks under his DJ alias for the latest Fabriclive mix release.

title: The Craft
summary: The San Francisco rap duo of Gift of Gab (aka Timothy Parker) and Chief Xcel (Xavier Mosley) return with a third album.

title: Last Days Of Wonder
summary: This is the first release in three years for the husband-and-wife duo of Brett and Rennie Sparks.

title: Twins
summary: This is the San Francisco rock singer's third release in 2012 (the other two were: Hair with White Fence and Slaughterhouse with his own band).

title: K Bay
summary: The first full-length solo release for the indie singer-songwriter features a guest appearance from Joseph "JoJo" Clarke.

title: Serfs Up!
summary: The English rock band moves to Domino for their third album.

title: A  Flame My Love, a Frequency
summary: The latest full-length release for the French artist known for using a viola da gamba changes to electronic instruments that include Moog effects pedals and Critter and Guitari synthesizers.

title: Apricity
summary: The fourth full-length release for the British psychedelic rock band was produced by Jason Falkner.

title: Rewind the Film
summary: Richard Hawley, Cate Le Bon, and Lucy Rose guest on the 11th full-length studio release from the Welsh alternative rock band.

title: Water
summary: This is the second full-length release for Berlin-based experimental electronic producer J'Kerian Morgan.

title: Monkey Minds in the Devil's Time
summary: The Beta Band singer self-produced 11 songs and Dan Carey worked on the other nine songs on Mason's politically-influenced second solo release.

title: Breaks in the Armor
summary: The sixth album for the indie rock band led by Archer of Loaf's Eric Bachmann was recorded at The Bakery with Matt Yelton.

title: Nashville
summary: The singer-songwriter follows his acclaimed effort '1972' with another album produced by Brad Jones. Don't be fooled by the title: it's not a country album, but rather, a farewell to the city Rouse has called home for the past decade (before moving to Spain).

title: The Wondershow Of The World
summary: This is Will Oldham's first Bonnie "Prince" Billy album to credit the Cairo Gang, who performed on the previous three Billy albums.

title: Welcome to Bobby's Motel
summary: The debut full-length release for the Montreal-based indie rock band was produced by Jonathan Schenke.

title: Butter
summary: The Scottish electronic artist releases his debut full-length album.

title: Hey Mr Ferryman
summary: The 10th full-length solo release for the former lead singer of American Music Club was produced by Bernard Butler.

title: Ruins
summary: The tenth studio release from Liz Harris as Grouper was mainly recorded in Portugal in 2011 on a 4-track.

title: One Breath
summary: The follow-up to the British singer-songwriter's Mercury Prize-nominated debut was produced by John Congleton.

title: Unglamorous
summary: Faith Hill and Tim McGraw guest on Lori McKenna's first album with a major label.

title: Love Keeps Kicking
summary: This is the third full-length release for the British indie punk band.

title: Reassemblage
summary: The second full-length release for the ambient duo of Spencer Doran and Ryan Carlile features guest appearances from  Matt Carlson, Miyako Koda, and Motion Graphics.

title: Down Like Gold
summary: The debut release for the Isle of Wight brother duo was recorded at a former water tower.

title: Tin Star
summary: The third full-length studio release for the Canadian singer-songwriter was produced by Dave Cobb.

title: I'll Sleep When You're Dead
summary: El-P's long-anticipated second solo disc features collaborations with Cat Power, Trent Reznor, Matt Sweeney, Aesop Rock, and The Mars Volta.

title: Robyn Hitchcock
summary: The latest solo release for the artist was produced with Brendan Benson with a full studio band that included Grant-Lee Phillips, Pat Sansone, Emma Swift, and Gillian Welch.

title: The Universal Want
summary: The first full-length studio release for the British alternative rock band in over 10 years was produced with Dan Austin.

title: Invisible Hour
summary: Recorded over four days, the 13th release for the singer-songwriter feature guest appearances from Lisa Hannigan as well as Kenneth Pattengale & Joey Ryan of The Milk Carton Kids.

title: A Ways Away

The band's name comes from an episode of the Chris Elliott sitcom "Get A Life."

title: Teflon Don
summary: Losing none of the momentum put in motion by his 2009 effort, Deeper Than Rap, Rick Ross keeps a very good thing going on Teflon Don, arguably his best album to date. You want rap-style luxury? Then Deeper is the better fit, but Teflon plays up the chilled and soulful elements of its predecessor, meaning Ross has graduated to a level where words like â€œorganicâ€ and â€œpoignantâ€ come into play. The former is best represented by â€œMayback Music IIIâ€ and itâ€™s swirling, â€˜70s-flavored dreamscape created by the J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League production team. Ross allows guests T.I. and Jadakiss to go first on the cut, then grabs his cigar for an uplifting story of ghetto triumph that goes from pushing to pleasing the folks (â€œParents never had a good job/Now itâ€™s black American Express cards"). When it comes to â€œpoignant,â€ the evidence is dotted throughout the album with the rapper reflecting on where heâ€™s been, and he often questions his own lust for fame. He chants the title to the opening â€œIâ€™m Not a Starâ€ as if it was a remindful mantra, but itâ€™s his new love of contrasts thatâ€™s really interesting, following Kanyeâ€™s swaggering on â€œLive Fast, Die Youngâ€ with â€œSeems to me we gettinâ€™ money for the wrong things/Look around, Maseratis for the whole team/Look at Haiti, children dyinâ€™ round the clock/Iâ€™d send a hundred grand but thatâ€™s a decent watchâ€. The familiar party and thugging tunes work too with â€œB.M.F. (Blowin' Money Fast),â€ â€œNo. 1,â€ and the mixtape favorite â€œMC Hammerâ€ -- now with added Gucci Mane verse -- all coming correct. Add all the Illuminati references in the Jay-Z team-up (â€œFree Masonâ€), a decent smoking song (â€œSuper Highâ€), and a track where Cee-Loâ€™s performance just might make you misty (â€œTears of Joyâ€), and itâ€™s obvious Rossâ€™ albums are no longer just vessels for his singles. ~ David Jeffries

summary: This is the second full-length release for the Montreal kraut-funk band that includes Jean-Sebastien Truchy, Sebastien Fournier, Eric Gingras and, Samuel Bobony.

summary: The second solo album for the folk singer was produced by Joe Henry.

title: Leveler
summary: The fourth studio album for the metal band from Pennsylvania was produced by Jason Suecof.

summary: This is the debut full-length album for British rapper/producer Obaro Ejimiwe.

The album picked up a great deal of acclaim in the UK when it was released in mid-2001, and finally secured U.S. distribution (through Emperor Norton) in early 2002.

summary: The surprise 17-track mixtape from the Canadian artist features guest appearances from Lil Wayne, PARTYNEXTDOOR, and Travi$ Scott was produced by Noah “40” Shebib and Matthew Jehu Samuels.

title: II

title: Moonshine Freeze

title: Shrink Dust
summary: The fifth full-length release for the Canadian is self-described as his country album.

summary: The UK indie rock group's fifth album.

summary: Thom Monahan produced the band's fourth studio album.

title: Dream a Garden

title: South of Reality
summary: The second full-length release for the experimental psychedelic rock duo of Les Claypool and Sean Lennon was self-produced.

One led by his long-time pianist Luis Perdomo, bassist Drew Gress, and drummer E.J. Strickland and the other led by trumpeter Ralph Alessi, pianist Geri Allen, bassist James Genus, and drummer Eric Harland who worked on his second album, From the Round Box.

title: Chance of Rain

title: Part II: The New December
summary: Fol Chen continues to embrace mystery and avoid the obvious on Part II: The New December. As on Part I: John Shade, Your Fortuneâ€™s Made, the enigmatic band makes a virtue out of indirectness, sending songs through secret passages and tunnels that end in hooks some distance from where they were expected. Thereâ€™s a strong experimental streak in the brainy way Fol Chen takes what seems like a straightforward idea and twists it into something completely different; like the Dirty Projectors, the group flirts with and subverts mainstream pop ideas, and like labelmates Cryptacize, theyâ€™ve got a flair for the deceptively simple. The band goes even further down the rabbit hole than on Part I, beginning The New December with some of its strangest music. â€œIn Ruinsâ€ contrasts deep, whispered vocals with lively girlish ones atop busy keyboards playing busy, vaguely Eastern-tinged melodies; â€œYour Curtain Callâ€ begins with breathy beats and woozy flutes, expanding into bells and a drunken sax solo before pulling back again; and â€œMen, Houses or Beastsâ€ tiptoes so slowly that it almost sounds like it was recorded at the wrong speed. Fittingly for a band so committed to disguising its identity, some of The New Decemberâ€™s best songs deal with miscommunication and missed connections. On â€œThe Holograms,â€ a tale of forgotten names and words doubling into optical illusions, bounces along on one of the albumâ€™s catchiest melodies, while the excellent â€œC/Uâ€ keeps its lovers apart despite its almost perversely straightforward beat. Likewise, the band buries some of its best songs on the albumâ€™s second half: â€œAdeline (You Always Look so Bored)â€â€™s sharp-tongued chamber pop recalls St. Vincentâ€™s abundant musical and lyrical wit, and â€œThey Came to Meâ€ boasts rubbery beats that are just as danceable as they are strange, and could be heard at a club with a trampoline for a dancefloor. How exactly these songs fit together with â€œHolesâ€â€™ delicate plucking and the title trackâ€™s pixelated folk might be locked in Fol Chenâ€™s brains, but even if there are more pieces of their puzzle-pop missing here than there were on John Shade, Your Fortuneâ€™s Made, The New December is never boring. ~ Heather Phares
