title: Ensemble Pearl
summary: Sunn 0)))'s Stephen O'Malley is joined by Michio Kurihara of Ghost, Boris drummer Atsuo, and William Herzog from Jesse Sykes & the Sweet Hereafter, plus Eyvind Kang and Timba Harris on Ensemble Pearl's debut release.

title: More Adventurous
summary: The Los Angeles indie-rockers make their major label debut with 'More Adventurous.' In the two years since their previous outing together, the band's Jenny Lewis contributed vocals to the debut from the Postal Service, while Blake Sennett and Jason Boesel released an album from their own side project, The Elected.

title: Hotspot
summary: The 14th full-length studio release for the British synth-pop duo features a guest appearances from Years & Years and was produced by Stuart Price.

title: 808s & Heartbreak
summary: The fourth album for the Grammy-winning rapper features Young Jezzy, Lil Wayne, Mr. Hudason, and Kid Cudi.

title: Rock or Bust
summary: The 16th full-length studio release for the Australian hard rock band was produced by Brendan O’Brien and its first with Stevie Young, who took over his uncle's role in 2014.

title: Lovesick Blues
summary: The first solo album in nearly eight years for the dB's Chris Stamey includes acoustic arrangements.

title: Stronger With Each Tear
summary: The latest album for the R&B singer features guest performers Drake, T.I., and Trey Songz as well as a song from the film "Precious."

title: Partie Traumatic
summary: The quintet from Jacksonville, Florida, releases its debut album produced by Bernard Butler.

title: Honeyblood
summary: The debut full-length release for the Scottish indie pop duo of Stina Tweeddale and Shona McVicar was produced by Peter Katis.

title: Slow Summits
summary: The first release since 1997’s Illumination for the Scottish indie pop band was produced by John McEntire and includes guest appearances from the Tenniscoats; Norman Blake and Gerard Love of Teenage Fanclub; and Stefan Schneider and Ronald Lippok of To Rococo.

title: Mirror II
summary: The third full-length release for the Australian trio was recorded in Bristol by producer John Parish.

title: Arrow
summary: The ninth full-length release for Sarah Lipstate as Noveller was recorded in Los Angeles.

title: Heza
summary: The third full-length studio release for the New Orleans-based duo of Grant Widmer and Ted Joyner is the first album on the Polyvinyl label.

title: Weird Sister
summary: The debut release for the Welsh noise pop band was produced by MJ of the Hookworms.

title: The Incredible True Story
summary: The second full-length studio release for the Maryland rapper features guest appearances from Big Lenbo, Jesse Boykins III, Dria, and Lucy Rose.

title: Woman
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the R&B/soul singer features production from 9th Wonder, David Banner, and Andre "Dre" Harris.

title: No Coast
summary: The first full-length studio release from the emo band in 16 years was produced by Will Yip.

title: Morgan Delt
summary: The debut full-length release for the California indie pop singer-songwriter was influenced by 1960s music.

title: The Blue Depths
summary: The latest album from the Indiana rock duo, now based in Berkeley, California.

title: Out My Window
summary: This is the debut album for the Candian producer/DJ.

title: Pay The Devil
summary: The singer-songwriter takes a stab at country music with this collection of a dozen covers and three originals.

title: Fever Breaks
summary: The 10th full-length studio release for the singer-songwriter was produced by Jason Isbell and features contributions from Amanda Shires and members of Isbell's the 400 Unit.

title: Permo
summary: The debut full-length release for the Scottish indie pop band was produced by Edwyn Collins.

title: The Deepest Lake
summary: The sixth full-length release for the Los Angels group was self-produced.

title: Palme
summary: The Icelandic singer-songwriter worked with Gunnar Orn Tynes of mum and Skuli Sverrisson on her fourth full-length release.

title: The Mystery of Heaven
summary: This is the second release for the year from the collaboration between Jozef Van Wissem and guitarist Jim Jarmusch.

title: In Ferneaux
summary: The latest release for Benjamin John Power's solo electronic project features two 20-minutes long tracks.

title: Spectre
summary: The latest release for the Slovenian group includes three songs originally released on its 2013 EP S.

title: Love Your Dum and Mad
summary: The debut full-length release for the British singer-songwriter was produced by Ben Hillier.

title: Wild Onion
summary: The second full-length release for the Chicago rock band was produced with R. Andrew Humphrey and Colin Croom.

title: Gallipoli
summary: The fifth full-length release for the indie folk band led by Zach Condon was produced by Gabe Wax.

title: Please Don't Be Dead
summary: The follow-up to the Oakland artist's Grammy Award-winning 2016 release was influenced in part by divisive political and social issues.

title: Brand New Abyss
summary: This is the second full-length release for the Washington state electro-pop duo of Khaela Maricich and Melissa Dyne.

title: Government Plates
summary: The third full-length studio release for the experimental rap group was self-released and posted as a free download. It was official release on iTunes on 14 January 2014.

title: Go Easy
summary: The third release for the Brisbane, Australian band is a mix of pop and psychedelic rock.

title: Flockaveli
summary: The rapper who worked with Gucci Mane on a few mixtapes releases his first official album.

title: Hymn To The Immortal Wind
summary: The fifth album for the Japanese experimental rock band was produced by Steve Albini.

title: One Armed Bandit
summary: The Norwegian group led by Lars Horntveth continues its jazz fusion of music styles on its latest album.

title: H-P1
summary: The latest album for the Brooklyn rock band led by Dave W. features a 17-minute-long track.

title: Ce
summary: The Brazilian superstar takes a stab at rock, backed by a much younger band and co-production by his son, Moreno.

title: Social Cues
summary: John Hill produces the Kentucky alt-rock band's fifth album, which features a collaboration with Beck.

title: Allo Darlin'
summary: The debut album for the London based indie pop band includes two Australian and two British members.

title: ACCA
summary: The second full-length release for the Paris-based British singer features guest appearances from Iggy Pop and Lakeith Stanfield.

title: Unfurl
summary: This is the second full-length release for the Australian, LA-based singer-songwriter.

title: Vaxis - Act I: The Unheavenly Creatures
summary: The Amory Wars epic continues in the self-produced ninth full-length studio release for the progressive rock band.

title: Writing of Blues & Yellows
summary: The debut full-length release for the British singer-songwriter was produced by Rich Cooper and Cam Blackwood.

title: Adventure
summary: The latest release for the Japanese pop-punk band sees the return of original drummer Atsuko Yamano.

title: Each Other
summary: The third full-length release for the Canadian singer-songwriter was produced by Marcus Paquin.

title: Mess
summary: The seventh full-length release for the rock trio was produced by band member, Angus Andrew.

title: Shout!
summary: The first release on the Blue Note label for the jam band is a double album with the second disc of the same songs as the first disc with guest singers including Elvis Costello, Dr. John, Toots Hibbert, Glenn Hughes, Ben Harper, Jim James, Myles Kennedy, Dave Matthews, Grace Potter, Ty Taylor, and Steve Winwood.

title: Vapor Trails
summary: Canada's favorite prog rockers return with their first album of new material in six years, eh.

title: Rome
summary: Inspired by Italian film scores from the 1960s and featuring guest vocalists Norah Jones and Jack White, Rome is producer Danger Mouse's pet project with Daniele Luppi.

title: Froot
summary: The third full-length studio release for the Welsh artist was recorded with a live band.

title: Dignity And Shame
summary: Velocity Girl's Sarah Shannon guests on Eric Bachmann's fourth Crooked Fingers release, which was co-produced by Martin Feveyear.

title: Long.Live.A$AP
summary: 2 Chainz, Action Bronson, Big K.R.I.T., Danny Brown, Drake, Joey Bada$$, Kendrick Lamar, Santigold, Schoolboy Q, Skrillex, and Yelawolf guest on the official debut studio release for the New York rapper.

title: There Is No End
summary: The posthumous release from the drummer features beats recorded before he passed away in 2020 and completed by producer Vincent Taeger and co-producer Vincent Taurelle with vocals from Nate Bone, Danny Brown, Nah Eeto, Jeremiah Jae, Koreatown Oddity, Lava La Rue, Lord Jah-Monte Ogbon, Marlowe, Ben Okri, Sampa The Great, Skepta, Tsunami, and Zelooperz.

title: Quit the Curse
summary: The debut full-length solo release for the Frontier Ruckus/Failed Flowers member was mixed by Collin Dupuis.

title: Built on Glass
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the Australian producer, songwriter, and singer Nick Murphy.

title: Radical Connector
summary: The German elecronica duo of Andi Toma and Jan St. Werner are back with their first LP in three years, combining distorted vocals and samples with their glitchy yet melodic--and sometimes even humorous--instrumentation.

title: Sorry I Make You Lush
summary: Wagon Christ is the alter-ego of prolific English electronica artist Luke Vibert (who also records under his own name and Plug).

title: The Cure
summary: The follow-up to 2000's 'Bloodflowers' sees Robert Smith & co. working with metal producer Ross Robinson (Limp Bizkit, Korn) for the first time (and apparently, he ate up so much of the recording budget that they couldn't afford an album cover artist).

title: Voice Of Treason
summary: If you think the concept of a guitar-drums blues duo from Detroit sounds a bit, well, familiar, consider this: Soledad Brothers guitarist Johnny Walker allegedly is responsible for teaching the White Stripes' Jack White how to play guitar. This is the Brothers' third studio LP.

title: Strays
summary: A reunited Jane's Addiction (sans bassist Eric Avery) is back with their first studio recording in 13 years.

title: L' Avventura
summary: Bassist Britta Phillips and guitarist Dean Wareham (each a member of the band Luna) offer a mix of originals and covers, including takes on songs by Madonna, the Silver Jews and the Doors, all produced by Tony Visconti (David Bowie, T. Rex).

title: Ego War
summary: Already being heralded as 2003's version of The Streets, the suburban London duo who compose the Audio Bullys combine everything from punk, ska, new wave, and house on this debut.

title: Beauty Party
summary: 'Beauty Party' represents experimental hip-hop artist Mike Ladd's second album in a planned trilogy, the first being 2000's 'Gun Hill Road' by The Infesticons. Unlike its predecessor, the Majesticons disc ventures into commercial rap territory (albeit with a satirical bent), attempting to skewer contemporary hiphop by beating it at its own game.

title: Amore del Tropico
summary: The San Diego-based band returns with their fourth album of dark, atmospheric music, following previous albums '1,' '2,' and, yes, '3' (c'mon guys, what happened to '4?'). This one is a concept album of sorts, about a murder mystery.

title: Musique Automatique
summary: This is the fifth LP for the French-pop-influenced,  Berlin-based duo of Francoise Cactus and Brezel Goring.

title: Star Kitty's Revenge
summary: This is the third solo album (and first since 1996) for neo-soul singer Joi Gilliam.

title: 4 Your Eyez Only
summary: The fourth full-length studio release for the North Carolina hip-hop artist includes co-production with such producers as Elite, Cardiak, Chargaux, Ron Gilmore, and Elijah Scarlett.

title: Strange Little Birds
summary: The sixth full-length release for the alternative rock band led by Shirley Manson was produced by Billy Bush.

title: We Are Nots
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the Memphis band that includes former Ex-cult bassist Natalie Hoffmann.

title: Hospitality
summary: The debut full-length release for the Brooklyn indie pop band includes some tracks from its 2008 EP of the same name.

title: I Sold Gold
summary: This is the second full-length for the Seattle-based band which consists solely of David Terry (and his drum machine) and has drawn comparisons to Grandaddy and the Flaming Lips.

title: Coming Apart
summary: The debut full-length release for Kim Gordon's post-Sonic Youth project is with guitarist Bill Nace.

title: Muzz
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the indie rock project that includes Interpol's Paul Banks, The Walkmen's Matt Barrick, and Bonny Light Horseman's Josh Kaufman.

title: Big Music
summary: The 16th studio release for the Scottish pop band features production from Gavin Goldberg, Steve Hillage, Steve Osborne, Owen Parker, and Andy Wright.

title: III
summary: The third release for the London-based Japanese quartet features King Midas Sound's Roger Robinson and Savages' Jehnny Beth.

title: The  Dissent of Man
summary: Joe Barresi produced the latest album for the southern California punk band who celebrates its 30th anniversary in 2010.

title: The Creatures In The Garden Of Lady Walton
summary: This is the first non-instrumental album for the group and features My Brightest Diamond's Shara Worden, The National's Matt Berninger, and Sufjan Stevens as guest singers. The songs were written in 2005 while Padma Newsome was working in Italy.

title: Immolate Yourself
summary: This is the third album for the Chicago-based duo of Josh Eustis and Charlie Cooper (who passed away on January 22, 2009).

title: Friendly Fires
summary: The debut full-length album for the British trio was self-produced.

title: Gem
summary: The fourth release for singer-songwriter Meghan Remy was produced by Slim Twig.

title: I Like It When You Sleep, For You Are So Beautiful Yet So Unaware of It
summary: The second full-length release for the British alternative rock band was produced by Mike Crossey.

title: Sasami
summary: The debut full-length solo release for the former member of Cherry Glazerr was recorded by Thomas Dolas and her brother JooJoo Ashworth.

title: Milk Famous
summary: The White Rabbits switch from Spoon's Britt Daniel to Mike McCarthy for production duties on its latest album.

title: Bliss Release
summary: The Australian psychedelic rock band's debut album won the Australian Music Prize award when the album was released in its native land in 2010.

title: Lost Themes III: Alive After Death
summary: Director/composer John Carpenter returns with son Cody Carpenter and godson Daniel Davies on his first non-soundtrack release in five years.

title: King Tuff
summary: The second release for King Tuff was produced by Bobby Harlow and is his first on the Sub Pop label.

title: Broken Boy Soldiers
summary: 'Soldiers' marks the debut for the new band consisting of the White Stripes' Jack White, fellow Detroit musician Brendan Benson, and members of the Greenhornes.

title: The  Canyon
summary: The seventh full-length studio release for the Utah rock band was influenced by the death of Rob McCracken's friend and was produced by Ross Robinson.

title: Seeing Things
summary: The Wallflowers' lead singer releases his debut solo album.

title: Brown Submarine
summary: Guided by Voices' Robert Pollard and Chris Slusarenko and Decemberists' John Moen release their debut album as the Boston Spaceships.

title: With Strings Live At Town Hall
summary: This 22-song live recording (taped at a New York City show in June, 2005) finds Mark Oliver Everett backed by a variety of instrumentalists and, yes, a string quartet.

title: Eraserland
summary: The sixth full-length release for Timothy Showalter as Strand Of Oaks features contributions from My Morning Jacket’s Tom Blankenship, Carl Broemel, Patrick Hallahan, Bo Koster, as well as Jason Isbell.

title: The Double Cross
summary: The Canadian rock band's 10th album was released on the 20th anniversary of its first show.

title: How About I Be Me (And You Be You)?
summary: The Irish singer-songwriter's ninth studio album was produced by her first husband, John Reynolds.

title: The Other
summary: The fourth full-length release for Kyle Thomas as King Tuff was self-produced and features contributions from Mikal Cronin, Jenny Lewis, Charles Moothart Kevin Morby, Greta Morgan, and Ty Segall.

title: Czarface Meets Metal Face
summary: The first full-length collaboration between Czarface [Wu-Tang Clan's Inspectah Deck and 7L & Esoteric] and MF Doom features guest appearances from Kendra Morris, Open Mike Eagle and Vinnie Paz.

title: Glass
summary: This is the second full-length release for Ryan Hunn as Illum Sphere.

title: Kamikaze
summary: The third full-length release for the Brooklyn punk rock band was produced by John Reis.

title: Olympic Mess
summary: The fourth full-length release for London-based experimental artist  Luke Younger was inspired by balearic disco, industrial, and dub techno music.

title: The MF Life
summary: The second album for the R&B/soul Canadian singer features guest appearances by J. Cole, B.o.B, John Legend, and T-Pain.

title: A Flash Flood of Colour
summary: The third album for the British band was produced by Dan Weller.

title: Our Thickness
summary: Mathew Adam Hart's quirky one-man bedroom-pop band (think Magnetic Fields) returns with a third album.

title: Romance Is Boring
summary: The latest album for the Welsh rock band was recorded in Connecticut and Seattle, with Xiu Xiu's Jamie Stewart, Parenthetical Girls' Zac Pennington, and Dead Science's Jherek Bischoff appearing as guests.

title: Sound Kapital
summary: The music project of Wolf Parade's Dan Boeckner and his wife Alexei Perry releases a third album influenced by Eastern European synthesizer sounds and noise pop.

title: Go to School
summary: The second full-length release for Brian and Michael D'Addario is a concept musical album about a chimpanzee named Shane raised a human boy and features guest appearances from Todd Rundgren and the D'Addario brothers' mother.

title: Fingers, Bank Pads and Shoe Prints
summary: This is the second full-length release for the Chicago footwork artist who is considered the founder of the style.

title: Sunlit Youth
summary: The third full-length release for the Los Angeles indie rock band was recorded in Hawaii, Malaysia, Nicaragua, Ojai, and Thailand.

title: Outrun
summary: The concept behind the full-length debut release from the French house producer Vincent Belorgay is how a man who crashed his Ferrari Testarossa in 1986, arises as a zombie in 2006 to make music and race cars.

title: A Certain Trigger
summary: A somewhat unusual signing for Warp Records, the guitar-oriented Maximo Park (who sound not unlike a cross between the Futureheads and Franz Ferdinand) make their full-length debut with this Paul Epworth-produced disc.

title: The Switch
summary: This is the second full-length studio release for Kim Gordon's post-Sonic Youth project with guitarist Bill Nace.

title: The 20/20 Experience
summary: The third solo release for the pop singer is his first in nearly seven years and was produced by Timbaland (two tracks with Timberlake and Jerome "J-Roc" Harmon).

title: Wire
summary: This is the 14th studio release for the British post-punk band led by Colin Newman.

title: The Mutt's Nuts
summary: The second full-length release for the London-based punk band led by Charlie Manning Walker was produced by Fucked Up's Jonah Falco.

title: Not Dark Yet
summary: The debut full-length collaboration between sisters Shelby Lynne and Allison Moorer features one original co-written song and was produced by Teddy Thompson.

title: Long Enough to Leave
summary: The second full-length release for the San Francisco Bay Area garage-pop band was produced by Kelley Stoltz.

title: Detours
summary: Sheryl Crow returns from an eventful few years with her latest record produced by Brian Bottrell, who also produced her debut.

title: Kurr
summary: The Icelandic group known for touring with Sigur Ros releases their debut album.

title: Big Wheel and Others
summary: The seventh full-length release for the indie singer-songwriter is a 22-track double-album featuring blues, country, folk, and jazz styles.

title: A Wasteland Companion
summary: M. Ward returns with his solo album featuring such guests as Howe Gelb of Giant Sand, Toby Leaman of Dr. Dog, Tom Hagerman of Devotchka, Mike Mogis of Bright Eyes, Steve Shelley of Sonic Youth, and She & Him collaborator Zooey Deschanel.

title: Meat + Bone
summary: The first release in eight years from the blues-rock trio was produced by frontman Jon Spencer.

title: Hyacinth
summary: The second full-length release for the Glasgow-based indie rock band is the first with Rachel Taylor, who took over for the departing Cal Donnelly.

title: All-Amerikkkan Bada$$
summary: The second full-length studio release for the New York rapper features guest appearances from Chronixx, Nyck Caution, Meechy Darko, J. Cole, Kirk Knight, Schoolboy Q, and Styles P.

title: Lament
summary: The German industrial band's latest release is music planned for a live performance commissioned by the city Diksmuide to commemorate the 100 year anniversary of the start of the First World War.

title: Pura Vida Conspiracy
summary: The sixth full-length release for the gypsy punk band led by Eugene Hütz was produced by Andrew Scheps.

title: Provider
summary: This is the US release of the debut solo album for the Constantines frontman.

title: Rooster Rag
summary: The blues rock band returns with its first new album in nine years.

title: The  Old Magic
summary: Growing older is the major theme of Nick Lowe's latest release, coproduced by Neil Brockbank and Robert Treherne.

title: Weareallgoingtoburninhellmegamixxx3
summary: With a follow-up to his 2007 I'll Sleep When You're Dead still in the works, El-P releases an album of instrumental tracks.

title: The Centre Cannot Hold
summary: The fifth full-length release for the Australian experimental artist was recorded over 10 days with contributions from Steve Albini, Lawrence English, Nico Muhly, Valgeir Sigurðsson, and Skuli Sverrisson.

title: There Is No Enemy
summary: The latest album for the indie rock band features  Quasi's Sam Coomes, Treepeople's Scott Schmaljohn, Butthole Surfers' Paul Leary, John McMahon, and Roger Manning as guest musicians.

title: Ringleader Of The Tormentors
summary: Tony Visconti (David Bowie) produced the suddenly prolific Moz's third release of the past two years.

title: Glider
summary: This is the second full-length solo release for the singer who has worked with Alela Diane, Efterklang, Laura Gibson, Horse Feathers, and Sharon Van Etten.

title: Generation Indigo
summary: The front woman of X-Ray Spex returns with her first solo album, staying true to her punk, reggae, and pop roots.

title: Art Brut vs. Satan
summary: The third album for the English band was produced by Black Francis (aka Frank Black).

title: Let's Build A Fire
summary: This is the third album for the James Baluyut-led indie rockers.

title: Delta Kream
summary: Dan Auerbach and Patrick Carney recorded covers of Mississippi hill country blues songs in Nashville over two sessions with Kenny Brown and Eric Deaton.

title: Me And Armini
summary: The latest album for the Icelandic singer was produced by Dan Carey.

title: Woman on the Internet
summary: The debut full-length release for the Irish singer-songwriter was produced by Pete Robertson.

title: The Long Walk
summary: Ben Greenberg and Michael Berdan add drummer Greg Foxfor for the band's third full-length release.

title: A Sentimental Education
summary: The New York City indie rock band return after breaking up in 2005 with an album of covers that includes songs by such artist as David Bowie, The Cure, Bob Dylan, Fleetwood Mac, Mercury Rev, Rolling Stones, and YES.

title: Long Lost Suitcase
summary: The latest studio release for the Welsh singer was produced by Ethan Johns.

title: I'm in Your Mind Fuzz
summary: This is the second full-length release for the Australian psychedelic rock band.

title: One Way, It's Every Way
summary: This is the second album of electronica-meets-indie-pop (falling somewhere between Manitoba and the Postal Service) from Mark Mitchell.

title: Soft Commands
summary: This solo disc from the Posies member features guest appearances from Jill Sobule and members of Velocity Girl, Oranger and the Posies.

title: The Ladybug Transistor
summary: This self-titled disc (the band's fifth studio recording) was recorded in Arizona with Calexico/Giant Sand producer Craig Schumacher.

title: Song In The Air
summary: This is the third LP for the Louisville-based emo band known for their strong live shows.

title: A Grown-Ass Man
summary: The sixth solo release for Yo La Tengo bassist James McNew finds him playing all of the instruments on 13 tracks that veer from style to style but share a certain lo-fi charm. There are ten originals and three covers, including the unlikely album-closing take on Thin Lizzy's "Cowboy Song."

title: Diamonds On The Inside
summary: Southern California native Harper has gained a cult following for his jam-band-like approach to roots rock. This is his fifth studio LP.

title: Does This Look Infected?
summary: The Toronto, Canada punk outfit returns with a follow-up to their successful 2001 debut, 'All Killer No Filler.'

title: One By One
summary: Former Nirvana drummer (and sometime Queens of the Stone Age drummer) Dave Grohl returns to the front of the stage for his role as vocalist, guitarist, and bandleader of the Foo Fighters on this, their fourth studio recording.

title: Out From Out Where
summary: This is the fourth album for the London-based, Brazilian-born jungle/breakbeat producer and DJ, following 2000's well-received 'Supermodified.'

title: The Magnificent
summary: You know him from his days supplying the beats to the Fresh Prince, but DJ Jazzy Jeff has finally stepped into the spotlight with this solo debut. Vocals are supplied by a variety of guests, including Jill Scott, Raheim, ?uestlove and J-Live.

title: Muzikizum
summary: The British house trio has been performing, producing, and remixing for ten years, but 'Muzikizum' represents their first album, highlighted by the breakout UK hit single "Lazy" featuring guest vocals from David Byrne.

title: New Favorite
summary: Alison Krauss and her band have gained popularity in recent months, thanks to the success of the O Brother, Where Art Thou? soundtrack (which featured the band's version of "I Am A Man Of Constant Sorrow" among other contributions). This is their first album since 1999's 'Forget About It.'

title: Live!
summary: Luna's first live recording compiles performances from New York's Knitting Factory and Washington D.C.'s 9:30 Club, including the band's final show with bassist Justin Harwood and one of its first with Harwood's replacement Britta Phillips. The disc includes songs from each of Luna's five studio albums, as well as one track ("4th of July") from frontman Dean Wareham's previous band, Galaxie 500.

title: Jade Bird
summary: Born in England but leaning, musically, toward Americana, the 21-year-old singer-songwriter follows her 2017 EP, "Something American," with this full-length debut.

title: Broken Side Of Time
summary: The debut full-length album for the band led by Swedish-born Petter Ericson Stakee and Terry Wolfers was produced by Mike McCarthy.

title: Black Rainbow Sound
summary: The third full-length release for the British duo of Ryan Needham and Liza Violet features a guest appearance by Brix Smith and was produced by Matt Peel.

title: Everything Else Matters
summary: The debut full-length release for the Russian shoegaze quintet was recorded in 2013.
The sixth album from the Dutch-Israeli singer-songwriter is a mix of choral arrangements, guitar, piano, and clarinet.

title: When Fish Ride Bicycles

John Porter (The Smiths) produces.

title: Dillatronic
summary: Curated by his mother, Ma Dukes, Dillatronic offers 41 rare instrumentals from the late Detroit hip-hop producer James "J Dilla" Yancey, with the focus being on his "electronic music influences," who are as much Kraftwerk as George Clinton. Case in point, the funky, slinky track seven included here -- none of the tracks are titled -- which slowly rocks back and forth like Clinton's solo hit "Atomic Dog," while the 26th cut comes off as a cross between Madlib and "Maggot Brain" with Funkadelic guitars spinning and swaying in a psychedelic manner. The latter track also strays from the "electronic music influences" concept, which happens with about a quarter of the album's tracks. Good thing too, as the chugging and organic track three is a much bigger surprise than the half-speed redo of "Trans Europe Express" that is track 20, plus the drifting, Janet Jackson-esque closer has little to do with electro but is likely to become a favorite with the target audience (a combination of the Dilla faithful, underground beatheads, and amateur MCs looking for mixtape productions). While the collection doesn't come with the purposeful feel of Donuts, it flows extremely well for a beat tape, and one released nine years after the artist passed. Add to that the amount of new flavors and unexpected twists (Was track 12 influenced by early dubstep? What was the plan for the dark and dense track 28?) plus crisp, clean recordings that beat the bootlegs, and Dillatronic is a necessary pickup for fans. ~ David Jeffries

title: Minotaur
summary: The Clienteleâ€™s 2009 album Bonfires on the Heath was one of the best, most hauntingly beautiful records of the bandâ€™s impressive career. So strong that it spawned an equally wonderful EP made up of songs recorded at the Bonfires sessions that were deemed suitable for the album itself. Hard to believe that they couldnâ€™t find room for the title track "Minotaur" as its fragile melody and sweetly swaying dynamics would have fit in perfectly. The same with the bouncing and sweet "Paul Verlaine"; it would have been one of the more memorable tracks there. That these songs were indeed left off only points out how good Bonfires was, and how easily the Clientele concoct note-perfect autumnal pop. Add in a moodily drifting cover of The West Coast Pop Art Experiment's creepy ballad from the late 60s,â€œAs the World Rises and Falls,â€ a couple of tracks that hit the usual Clientele sweet spot between heartbreak and tender melancholy, and a long spoken word ramble from leader Alasdair MacLean, and you have a record that rises above stopgap or left-overs status. Minotaur is as essential as anything else the band has released and whether as part of Bonfires or on its own, the record stands as a welcome addition to their legacy as one of the great indie pop bands of their era. ~ Tim Sendra

title: Closer Apart
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the collaboration between South African producer Okzharp and Die Antwoord's Manthe Ribane.

While the title track "Tour De France" was released as a single in 1983 (and is found here in four new versions), the remaining 8 tracks are brand new compositions.

title: Alive To Every Smile

title: Rain On Lens
summary: This is Bill Callahan's follow-up to 2000's acclaimed 'Dongs of Sevotion.'

title: G.O.A.T. Featuring James T. Smith: The Greatest of All Time
Personality (One Was A Spider, One Was A Bird)
summary: This is the second album for the Australian band led by Luke Steele.

title: LP5

title: Unreal

title: This Generation

the 13th release for the avant-garde Norwegian trio of Arve Henriksen, Helge Sten (aka Deathprod) and Ståle Storløkken was recorded from the music coming out from its stage PA system.

title: Shulamith

summary: The second full-length release for the British indie-pop group was produced by Marta Salogni.

He tends to get labeled an "eccentric" by the music press, with frequent Syd Barrett comparisons.

title: Cheers

title: Welcome To The Monkey House

Rex producer Tony Visconti, and, well, Evan Dando.

title: Finisterre

title: Jump Leads

This studio effort (on the band's own 23 label) follow's last year's mix album 'Another Late Night,' and is their first album to feature vocals, courtesy of Steve Edwards, who sings on four tracks.

title: Music Is A Hungry Ghost

Here, they combine with New York turntablist I-Sound for their first release on Mute Records.

title: Surrounded By Silence

title: Seasons on Earth

title: The Hazards Of Love

title: Render Another Ugly Method

title: CLPPNG

title: The Fall

title: Dear Life

title: Irreal

title: Summer Through My Mind

title: Sport

title: Burn The Maps

title: Volcano

summary: The major-label debut from the British-influenced rockers from Los Angeles.

The Courage Of Others

summary: The Danish quintet's third album was produced by  Fridolin.

summary: The second full-length release from the country trio was produced by Dann Huff.

title: Alela Diane & Wild Divine

title: Song Of The Pearl
summary: The David Heumann-led band releases its latest album.

title: I Can't Go On, I'll Go On
summary: This is the first album for the Los Angeles-based power-pop band formerly known as The Brokedown.

title: Ahead Of The Lions

summary: The San Francisco folk band release their fifth full-length album.

title: Good Girl Gone Bad
summary: The singer collaborated with Timbaland, Justin Timberlake and Ne-Yo for her third album.

title: Born Under Saturn
summary: The London-based Scottish quartet's follow-up to its Mercury-nominated debut release was recorded in a professional studio.

title: Beak>
summary: The debut album for the trio from Bristol was written in 12 days.

title: The Resistance
summary: The fifth album for the English rock trio was produced entirely by the band.

title: Black Cherry
summary: This sophomore LP from the UK duo of vocalist Allison Goldfrapp and multi-instrumentalist Will Gregory follows their acclaimed 2000 debut, 'Felt Mountain.'

title: These Four Walls
summary: The debut album for the Scottish indie-rock quartet.

title: Tomorrow's Modern Boxes

Here, on their full-length debut, they offer 10 brand-new tracks. (Yes, the period at the end of their name is necessary.)

title: Miss Fortune
summary: This is the critically-acclaimed Alabama singer's third album, and first for her new label Universal South.

summary: Believe it or not, these guys have been around for over 15 years now, and this is their eighth release (and first since 1998's 'Dizzy Up The Girl').

title: Too True

title: Natural History
summary: The second full-length release for the Baltimore rock band was produced by J Robbins of The Office of Future Plans.

title: Lifer
summary: The third full-length release for the Baltimore-based noise rock band led by Andrew Laumann was produced by Travis Harrison.

title: Disc-Overy
summary: The London rapper makes his debut of hip-hop and pop jams.

title: Lust Lust Lust
summary: The Danish duo's latest album features a 3D cover.

title: Picture You
summary: The third studio release for the Swedish five-piece band was recorded in three days.

title: False Idols

title: Ex

summary: This is the third studio album for the French synth-rock band.

summary: Alex Willner's debut album for his solo project, Loops of Your Heart, features synth-based electronic music.

title: Crownsdown
summary: The rap duo releases their first studio album in seven years.

title: Sol-Angel And The Hadley St. Dreams
summary: The sophomore album for the younger sister of Beyonce Knowles.

And while those words are sure to excite fans of the bald one's 70s classics such as 'Taking Tiger Mountain (By Strategy),' his first vocal album in 15 years is much closer in sound and mood to more recent efforts as well as the final handful of tracks on 'Eno Box II: Vocals' (the latter's "Under" even appears again on this disc).

Offering

title: Tribal

summary: This is the debut LP for the new project from Chris Lopez (Rock*A*Teens).

title: Beak 2
summary: This is the second release for the side project of Portishead's Geoff Barrow.

summary: The English electronic duo releases its ninth album, which was also released as a download earlier this year.

title: A Colores
summary: This is the fourth album for the San Diego, Calif. instrumental post-rock outfit.

(The Hockey Song)," features a vocal spot from David Letterman, of all people).

This is his third solo album, and features guest appearances by Evan Dando, Mogwai, Bono, and Photek.

title: Death Becomes Her

title: A Strange Arrangement

title: Romance

title: Worldwide

title: Gumption
summary: This is the debut full-length release for Kansas singer-songwriter Taryn Miller was produced by Nicolas Vernhes.

title: He Thinks He's People
summary: The Pinback co-founder releases his latest solo album.

title: Archive Material

title: Electric Lines
summary: The debut full-length solo release for the Hot Chip artist-producer features a guest appearance from SLO (Jess Mills).

title: T R O U B L E

title: Holdin' the Bag

title: Array 1 [EP]

title: Inclusions

title: I Can Wonder What You Did with Your Day

title: The Digging Remedy

title: Revelation

title: Blazing Gentlemen

title: Something Shines
summary: This is the third solo release for the former Stereolab singer.

title: What The Toll Tells
summary: This is the second album (and Saddle Creek debut) for the San Francisco duo of Adam Stephens and Tyson Vogel.

title: From A Birds Eye View

title: Watch The Fireworks

title: Perch Patchwork
summary: Maps & Atlasesâ€™ second EP, You and Me and the Mountain, found the band moving in a lighter direction than the mathematical frenzy of their first EP Trees, Swallows, Houses. Their first full-length sees them fully morphed into a sophisticated indie pop group. Perch Patchwork is a bold debut, filled with bombastic arrangements, twisting modal progressions, and percussive layers. The skill set is high, but itâ€™s far less showy. Guitarists will still be enthralled by Dave Davidson's and Erin Elders' fingertapping, but acoustics take precedent, and moderately slow tempos maintain the album's balladic feel. If Trees, Swallows, Houses felt like a cousin to Don Cab or Hella, their first Barsuk outing has adapted the organic spirit of their Northwestern labelmates (particularly that of Menomena, the Long Winters, and John Vanderslice.) Of course, with Maps & Atlases' virtuosic chops and syncopated leanings, they kind of resemble BLK JKS or Minus the Bear, albeit with a Jethro Tull influence. Trendy South African rhythms and austere strings spin a web around Davidsonâ€™s poetic lyrics, and in this intricate, introspective setting, their talent becomes very clear. ~ Jason Lymangrover

title: Blown Away
summary: The fourth studio album for the Grammy-winning country singer was produced by Mark Bright.

title: Asylum
summary: Chicago's hard rock arena-headliners return with another album of heavy metal hits that recall early Metallica and Iron Maiden while maintaining their trademark dark sound.

title: Crash Love
summary: The eighth full-length album for the rock band was produced by Joe McGrath and Jacknife Lee.

title: Rockwell
summary: The debut full-length album for the singer was produced by Steve Albini.

title: Memory Man
summary: London-based singer-songwriter and multi-instrumentalist Matt Hales returns with a second album following two years of touring in support of his debut 'Strange And Beautiful.'

title: Shine
summary: Brendan O'Brien produced the singer's first post-Phish solo record.

title: Vol. 4 :: Slaves of Fear
summary: The fourth full-length studio release for the Los Angeles noise rock band was produced by Lars Stalfors.

title: Woodstock
summary: The eighth full-length release for the indie rock band was recorded twice [they discarded a majority of the first session] with production from Danger Mouse, John Hill, Mike D, and Ammar Malik.

title: Ladyhawke
summary: The debut album for the New Zealander Pip Brown.

title: Twilight Of The Innocents
summary: The fifth and last full album for the UK band. In the future they will release only singles.

title: Odyssey
summary: Linda Perry and Susan Sontag (!) penned songs for the dance duo's belated sophomore release, which also features production from Tony Hoffer and Mirwais.

title: Wild Nights
summary: The second full-length release for the British quartet was recorded by Dave Catching in Joshua Tree.

title: Rapping With Paul White
summary: This is Paul White's first full-length project with vocals, which features Nancy Elizabeth, Danny Brown, Homeboy Sandman, Guilty Simpson, Jehst, Marv Won, Moe Pope, and Tranqill.

title: Pigeons
summary: The second album for the rock quintet from Brooklyn, New York was produced and recorded by the band in just over four months.

title: Funk Wav Bounces, Vol. 1
summary: The fifth full-length release for the Scottish electronic producer features guest appearances from A-Trak, Big Sean, D.R.A.M., Future, Ariana Grande, Kehlani, Khalid, John Legend, Lil Yachty, Migos, Nicki Minaj, Frank Ocean, PARTYNEXTDOOR, Katy Perry, Jessie Reyez, ScHoolboy Q, Travis Scott, Snoop Dogg, Takeoff, Pharrell Williams, and Young Thug.

title: Canopy Glow
summary: The second album for the Chicago-based band is its first on the Anticon label.

title: Duper Sessions
summary: The Norwegian artist (backed here by The Faces Down Quartet) remakes himself as a cabaret singer, with a disc full of jazz-pop tunes including a cover of the standard "Night and Day."

title: Once Upon A Little Time
summary: Members of Portishead and The Bad Seeds guest on the multi-instrumentalist's third solo outing.

title: Love for Sale
summary: Tony Bennett and Lady Gaga reunite for an album of Cole Porter songs accompanied by the Brian Newman Quintet with arrangements by Marion Evans & Jorge Callandrelli.

title: Transistor Rhythm
summary: This is the debut full-length album for British juke producer Tony Williams under the Addison Groove name.

title: Names of North End Women
summary: The collaboration between Lee Ranaldo and Raül Refree features little to no guitars.

title: Lookout Low
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Chicago garage-rock band was produced by Ethan Johns.

title: Sondre Lerche
summary: The Norwegian songwriter's self-titled sixth album features collaborations with Midlake percussionist McKenzie Smith and experiments with multiple genres, including jazz and bossa nova.

title: The Five Ghosts
summary: The Canadian indie rock band's first album on Soft Revolution was produced by Tom McFall.

title: Together We're Heavy
summary: Although the Dallas-based robe-wearing collective (who number close to 30) recorded their buzz-generating debut in just two days, this sophomore effort is the result of a full year in the studio. (Presumably, it's a very large studio.) Eric Feldman (Sparklehorse) and The Speekers produced.

title: This Is For Real
summary: 'This Is For Real' is the full-length debut for the trashy electro-punk outfit out of Sheffield, England.

title: Love And Distance
summary: The Portland, Ore. duo of Brandon Summers and Benjamin Weikel are back with their third album, and first for Sub Pop.

title: Last Night
summary: Combining blues, R&B, jazz and funk influences, this latest offering from the ever-changing 4AD group headed by Warren Defever, like its predessor (2001's 'Someday My Blues Will Cover The Earth'), features the vocals of Lovetta Pippen. Included among the originals here are covers of The Equals' "Teardrops," Ida's "Maybe," and Jimi Hendrix's "Train."

title: Cruelty Without Beauty
summary: Yes, it's *that* Soft Cell, the English band that brought you early 80s hits such as "Tainted Love" and "Sex Dwarf." Their first release since 1984's 'This Last Night in Sodom,' 'Cruelty Without Beauty' offers 12 brand-new tracks from the reunited duo of Dave Ball and Marc Almond.

title: Dirty Child
summary: The Los Angeles singer/songwriter's eclectic debut album comes after cuts on the soundtracks to "Bridget Jones's Diary" and "Shallow Hal."

title: Sleeping On Roads
summary: This is the first solo release from Slowdive and Mojave 3 frontman Neil Halstead, and includes occasional guest contributions from the likes of his bandmate Ian McCutcheon and Locust's Mark Van Hoen.

title: OST
summary: The soundtrack to the Cameron Crowe comedy features music from the 1970's, including tracks from Simon & Garfunkel, The Who, The Allman Brothers Band, Elton John, and David Bowie (a cover of Velvet Underground's "I'm Waiting For The Man"), and one original track, from the movie's fictitious Stillwater.

title: Ester
summary: The debut full-length release for the British quartet was self-recorded by the band.

title: Not Waving, But Drowning
summary: The English hip-hop artist follows his Mercury Prize-nominated 2017 debut with his second LP. And it's perhaps the first rap album in history to feature a song about celebrity chef Yotam Ottolenghi. Collaborators include Sampha, Jorja Smith, Jordan Rakei, and Tom Misch.

title: See Mystery Lights
summary: This is the third album for the duo from Oregon led by Jona Bechtolt.

title: Uneasy Laughter
summary: The second full-length release for the Los Angeles post-punk trio was produced by Alex Newport.

title: Birdie
summary: The second full-length side/solo project for Modern Baseball's Jake Ewald was produced by Ian Farmer.

title: Nights Out
summary: The British electronic artist produced his sophomore album.

title: World Peace Is None of Your Business
summary: The 10th solo studio release for the British indie singer-songwriter was produced by Joe Chiccarelli and recorded in France.

title: An Odd Entrances
summary: The third release in 2016 for the rock band led by John Dwyer is a companion album to A Weird Exits featuring six tracks recorded from the same sessions.

title: ii
summary: This is the debut release for the side project of Efetrklang with Finnish percussionist Tatu Ronkko.

title: Buzzard
artist: Margot & the Nuclear So and So's
summary: Described as cinematic chamber pop, this Indianapolis band's third album features heavier electric guitar rock with a mix of unique multiple instrumentation.

title: Ti Amo
summary: The first new release in four years for the French rock band was self-produced.

title: Ogilala
summary: The second full-length solo release for The Smashing Pumpkins frontman (but the first under his full given name) was produced with Rick Rubin.

title: Dance Mother
summary: The debut album for the duo from Brooklyn was produced by Dave Sitek.

title: Sea Of Cowards
summary: The Jack White-led rock band releases its follow-up to its 2009 debut, "Horehound."

title: The World Is Yours
summary: The legend of Lemmy lives on as Motorhead releases their 20th album on the year of their 35th anniversary, continuing their hard rock, heavy metal roller-coaster ride.

title: Minimum Rock N Roll
summary: The fourth full-length release for the band led by Ian Svenonius was recorded in Oregon and mixed by Brendan Canty in DC.

title: Dub Egg
summary: This is the Austin band's second full-length release and its debut for Matador Records.

title: Burned Mind
summary: Their first Sub Pop release finds the noisy Detroit band as a threesome, with founder Nate Young joined (as he has been since 2000) by Aaron Dilloway and John Olson.

title: Everybody's Everything
summary: The second posthumous release for the rapper features some previously released tracks as well as some unreleased ones that features collaborations with Era, Gab3, iLoveMakonnen, Lil Tracy, and Rich the Kid.

title: The  False Alarms
summary: Produced by Samuel Bing and Julian Wass, the third release for the Los Angeles pop collective features Sinosa Loa on lead vocals.

title: King Animal
summary: The sixth studio album for the rock band led by Chris Cornell is its first release of new music in 16 years.

title: The Black Session [Live]
summary: The live album was recorded in Paris on May 10, 2011, and includes tracks from Red Barked Tree as well as songs from earlier releases.

title: Human Energy
summary: The latest full-length solo release for Travis Stewart as Machinedrum features guest appearances from Tosin Abasi, Jesse Boykins III, D?WN, Kevin Hussein, Rochelle Jordan, MeLo-X, and Ruckazoid.

title: Red
summary: This is the second full-length album for the Norwegian electronic duo.

title: In the Blue Light
summary: The latest release for the singer-songwriter features new arrangements on 10 songs that span his career and features contributions from such artists as Jack DeJohnette, Bill Frisell, Steve Gadd, Wynton Marsalis, and yMusic.

title: Stone Temple Pilots
summary: The Grammy-winning California rock band led by Scott Weiland returns with its first album in nearly a decade.

title: Estoile Naiant
summary: The fourth full-length release for the British electronic producer is his first on the Wrap label.

title: In The Absence Of Truth
summary: This fourth LP for the metal band follow's 2004's acclaimed 'Panopticon' as well as an opening slot on Tool's latest tour.

title: How We Operate
summary: The UK rockers' fifth studio album is their first to utilize an outside producer, Gil Norton (Pixies, Foo Fighters).

title: Gold Medal
summary: The Donnas' second major-label effort was produced by Butch Walker (Avril Lavigne, Injected).

title: 21st Century Breakdown
summary: The eighth studio album for the band was produced by Butch Vig.

title: You Hear Georgia
summary: The seventh full-length studio release for the Atlanta rock band was produced by Dave Cobb and features guest appearances from Jamey Johnson and Warren Haynes.

title: Buoys
summary: The sixth full-length solo release for Noah Lennox as Panda Bear was co-produced and co-mixed with Rusty Santos.

title: Icarus Falls
summary: The second full-length solo release for the former One Direction singer features guest appearances from Nicki Minaj and Timbaland.

title: Felt
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Canadian quartet was self-produced and mixed by John Congleton.

title: Blast Off Through the Wicker
summary: The full-length debut release for the side project of Here We Go Magic's Luke Temple was recorded on a four-track tape recorder and was inspired by his move to California.

title: The  Divine Feminine
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Pittsburgh rapper feature gusset appearances from Bilal, CeeLo Green, Ariana Grande, Kendrick Lamar, Njomza, Anderson .Paak, and Ty Dolla $ign.

title: Monolith of Phobos
summary: The full-length debut from the collaboration between Primus bassist Les Claypool and Sean Lennon was written over two weeks at Claypool's house in Northern California.

title: Keep It Together
summary: The third full-length release for the sister duo was produced by Paul Mahern.

title: Discreet Desires
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the German electronic producer.

title: Hermits on Holiday
summary: This is the debut release for the collaboration between Cate Le Bon and White Fence's Tim Presley.

title: Sonic Soul Surfer
summary: Self-produced, the seventh full-length studio release from the blues artist features contributions from Luther Dickinson, Georgina Leach, Dan Magnusson, and Ben Miller.

title: Tracker
summary: The eighth full-length solo release for the former Dire Straits lead singer was produced with Guy Fletcher.

title: Playland
summary: The second full-length solo release for The Smiths' former guitarist was written while he was on tour.

title: Favorite Waitress
summary: The tenth release for the upstate New York folk quintet was produced by Jeremy Backofen in Omaha, Nebraska.

title: Sky Swimming
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the British duo of Amelia Rivas and Christian Pinchbeck.

title: Caramel
summary: The second full-length release for the New Zealand singer includes influences from funk, jazz, and psychedelic pop.

title: Golden Suits
summary: The debut solo release for the Department of Eagles co-founder Fred Nicolaus was produced with Fraser McCulloch.

title: Walk Through Exits Only
summary: The debut solo project from the Pantera and Down frontman with Bennett Bartley, Jose Manuel "Blue" Gonzales, and Marzi Montazeri as The Illegals was co-produced with Michael Thompson.

title: Oak Island
summary: This is the second solo release for The War On Drugs' Dave Hartley as Nightlands.

title: Dear...
summary: The debut album for the British singer-songwriter was recorded in his bedroom.

title: New Blood
summary: The former Genesis singer rerecorded some of his songs with a 46-piece orchestra conducted by Ben Foster.

title: Black and White
summary: The second album for the British rapper features guest appearances by Etta Bond, Chipmunk, Example, Darren B, Alex Mills, Daley, and Ed Sheeran.

title: Together/Apart
summary: Benjamin Laub, aka as Grieves, releases his third album produced by Budo.

title: Helioscope
summary: The post-rock band from Leeds, England, releases its second album produced by John Congleton.

title: Factorycraft
summary: The Scottish trio that won a Scottish BAFTA for its cybraphon (an interactive "mechanical band in a box") releases its third album.

title: Foreign Landscapes
summary: The follow-up to the German artist's 2008 album Ferndorf was recorded with San Francisco's Magik*Magik Orchestra.

title: The Big Black And The Blue
summary: This is the debut album for the Swedish teenage sisters.

title: Something For All Of Us...
summary: Broken Social Scene cofounder Brendan Canning releases his first solo album as a part of the "Broken Social Scene Presents" series.

title: Backwoods Barbie
summary: Dolly Parton's first record on her own label features songs that will appear in the musical version of "9 to 5."

title: Invitation Songs
summary: The Seattle-based band featuring ex-Pretty Girls Make Graves' Derek Fudesco releases their first album.

title: The Inspiration
summary: The Atlanta rapper's second Def Jam album includes contributions from Three 6 Mafia, Timbaland, Ludacris, T.I., and Young Buck.

title: Death In The Garden, Blood On The Flowers
summary: This is the second LP for the five-piece California indie pop band.

title: Master Of Disaster
summary: Jim Dickinson produced this 21st album for Hiatt, which finds him backed by members of the North Mississippi Allstars.

title: Faded Seaside Glamour
summary: 'Glamour' is the debut disc for the English band led by singer Greg Gilbert, whose voice has drawn him numerous comparisons to the Cocteau Twins' Liz Fraser (as odd as that may sound).

title: Shadows Collide With People
summary: The Red Hot Chili Peppers guitarist returns with a follow-up to his 2001 solo release, 'To Record Only Water For Ten Days.'

title: Team Boo
summary: This is the third album from the husband-wife duo of Kori Gardner (keyboards) and Jason Hammel (drums). Spoon's Jim Eno produced, along with John Croslin.

title: Oaklandazulasylum
summary: This solo release from the anticon collective's Jonathan Wolf (aka Why?), also a member of cLOUDDEAD, sees the experimental rapper mixing in a healthy dose of indie guitar with beats and samples that venture from lo- to hi- fi.

title: Keep On Your Mean Side
summary: "Coincidentally" released on the same day as the fourth album by the White Stripes, to whom the Kills are frequently compared, 'Mean Side' is the debut full-length for the UK blues-rock duo of VV (aka Alison Mosshart) and Hotel, who are backed by a drum machine (a la the Raveonettes).

title: Daybreaker
summary: The English singer-songwriter's third LP features quite an array of guests, including Ryan Adams, Emmylou Harris, and the Chemical Brothers (who have utilized Orton's vocals on several of their own albums). Another longtime collaborator, William Orbit, appears for one track, with the remainder of the mixing duties falling to Everything But The Girl's Ben Watt.

title: By The Way
summary: Although their ride has been rocky at times, the Los Angeles band is nearing its 20th anniversary. (And if you grew up listening to the band, doesn't that make you feel old.) This, their eighth album, finds the Chili Peppers working with producer Rick Rubin.

title: Loudboxer
summary: The Netherlands-based techno artist returns with his fifth album, which is less experimental than previous efforts, instead offering a seamless set of hardcore techno.

title: In The Afternoon
summary: The third and final album by the current lineup of this Chicago-based indie band (band member and Aesthetics label head Ken Dyber is leaving the group) includes 10 new tracks, featuring the alternating male/female vocals of Joseph Costa and Lindsay Anderson alongside the band's moody, haunting sound.

title: Buzzkunst
summary: The Buzzcocks are back. Well, almost. Pete Shelley and Howard Devoto, founding members of that seminal punk band, have recorded together for the first time in over 25 years, resulting in these 14 brand-new electronica-laden tracks.

title: The Lemonheads
summary: The Evan Dando-led band (now down to a trio) returns with its first studio disc in ten years. J Mascis guests.

title: Painting of a Panic Attack
summary: The fifth full-length release for the Scottish indie rock band was produced by The National's Aaron Dessner.

title: Minor Love
summary: Heavily influenced by the likes of Lou Reed and the Velvet Underground, Adam Green (the alternative-folk singer/songwriter better known for his stint with the lo-fi indie group Moldy Peaches) returns with his sixth studio album.

title: Takes
summary: The third album for the London artist features covers of songs by such artists as Bjork, Aphex Twin, and PJ Harvey.

title: Unorthodox Jukebox
summary: The second full-length release for the singer-songwriiter/producer includes production by Jeff Bhasker, Diplo, Paul Epworth, Mark Ronson, The Smeezingtons, and Andrew Wyatt.

title: Buck The World
summary: Eminem, Dr. Dre, 50 Cent and Hi-Tek are among the producers on the rapper's second LP. Young Jeezy, T.I. and Snoop Dogg also guest.

title: Strange Pleasures
summary: The second release for the London-based indie pop band led by Greg Hughes was influenced by 1980s pop music.

title: Free To Stay
summary: 'Free To Stay' is the second record for the indie-pop duo of sisters Chloe (drums) and Asya (keyboards, vocals), who have opened for Death Cab for Cutie, Pearl Jam, Sufjan Stevens, The Go! Team and others, and who just happen to be 12 and 14 years old.

title: Long Wave
summary: The ELO frontman releases a covers album of songs that inspired him, including Bobby Darin's "Beyond the Sea," Fain & Webster's "Love Is a Many Splendored Thing," Etta James' "At Last," Rodgers and Hammerstein's "If I Loved You," Rodgers & Hart's "Bewitched, Bothered and Bewildered," and the Rolling Stones' "Mercy, Mercy."

title: Kelis Was Here
summary: The singer's fourth album features production from will.i.am, Cee-Lo, Linda Perry, Max Martin and Raphael Saadiq (but, for the first time, not the Neptunes). Husband Nas also guests.

title: Release Me
summary: Lyle Lovett's final album with Curb Records features guest appearances from k.d. lang, Kat Edmonson, and Sara and Sean Watkins.

title: Sketches from the Book of the Dead
summary: The Australian artist releases his first solo album since leaving the Bad Seeds.

title: The Cautionary Tales of Mark Oliver Everett
summary: The latest release from the band led by Mark Oliver Everett was inspired by lost love.

title: Soul is Heavy
summary: The third album for the German-Nigerian singer features guest appearances from Black Thought of The Roots and Ms. Dynamite.

title: O Soundtrack My Heart
summary: The Australian group releases its first international effort on Warp Records, which offered them a 16-album contract.

title: Southsiders
summary: The theme of pain and hope continues on the sixth full-length studio release from the Minnesota indie rap duo of MC Slug and producer DJ Ant.

title: Sun Structures
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the psych rock-inspired British quartet led by James Bagshaw and Tom Warmsley.

title: Time Team
summary: This is the debut full-length album for British artist Greg Feldwick as Slugabed.

title: Mean Everything To Nothing
summary: The second full-length album for the indie-rock band from Atlanta was produced by Joe Chicarelli.

title: Colin Meloy Sings Live!
summary: The Decemberists lead singer releases his live solo album featuring songs from his 2006 tour.

title: To Syria with Love
summary: The third full-length release for the Syrian artist features more elements from electronic and techno music.

title: Dissolver
summary: TV On The Radio's Kyp Malone returns to his other band, Iran, to release its third album.

title: The Trip
summary: With Stereolab on hiatus, Laetitia Sadier returns to release her first solo album.

title: The Boxer
summary: The solo debut from Bloc Party singer/guitarist pushes boundaries with a blend of raw rock and energetic electro-pop.

title: Still on My Mind
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the British singer-songwriter was produced with (her brother) Rollo Armstrong, Simon Hulbert and Ryan Laubscher.

title: Eight
summary: Berlin-based Canadian Scott Monteith's eighth techno dub album as Deadbeat features guest appearances from Dandy Jack, Mathew Jonson, and Danuel Tate.

title: Buffalo
summary: The New Zealand indie rock band releases its fourth studio album.

title: O
summary: The third album for the indie rock band was produced by Mike Mogis.

title: Wrath Of Circuits
summary: This is the full-length debut for the Durham, NC dance-punk outfit led by Finn Cohen.

title: The Man Upstairs
summary: The British singer-songwriter worked with producer Joe Boyd on his 20th full-length solo release that includes covers and new original songs.

title: Mother
summary: Co-produced with Ben Harper, the debut solo release for the Dixie Chicks singer is a rock-influenced covers album of songs by such artists as Jeff Buckley, Patty Griffin, Pink Floyd, and The Jayhawks.

title: The Only Thing I Ever Wanted
summary: The London duo of Galia Durant and Carim Clasmann--who have benefitted from recent American TV exposure--return with a second album of electronica and funny noises.

title: Indigo
summary: The fourth full-length release for indie pop project of Jack Tatum was produced with Jorge Elbrecht.

title: Vol 3: (The Subliminal Verses)
summary: Rick Rubin produced this third LP for the popular mask-wearing Des Moines-based metal outfit, who are set to headline Ozzfest this summer.

title: How Sweet It is
summary: The onetime budding star (you remember "One Of Us," right?) returns with an album of covers of classic soul and R&B tunes from the 1960s and 70s.

title: Since We've Become Translucent
summary: This is the eighth release from the nearly 15-year-old Seattle band, and it features new instrumentation (a horn section) and a new bass player (Guy Maddison, replacing departed founding member Matt Lukin).

title: Nellyville
summary: The St. Louis rapper follows up the massive success of his 2000 debut LP 'Country Grammar' with 19 new tracks cut from the same cloth, including the Neptunes-produced single "Hot In Here." Justin Timberlake guests on one track.

title: After Everything Now This
summary: Over two years in the making, 'After Everything' is the twelfth album from the Australian band, still best known for their 1988 hit "Under The Milky Way."

title: Sword Of God
summary: This is the fourth release for Quasi, which features Sam Coomes (formerly of The Donner Party, and sometimes bandmate of Elliott Smith and Built to Spill) and Sleater-Kinney's Janet Weiss.

title: Flowers
summary: This is the third album from the group since founding members Ian McCulloch and Will Sergeant reunited in 1997.

title: Queen
summary: The fourth full-length release for the rapper features guest appearances from Eminem, Foxy Brown, Future, Ariana Grande, Labrinth, Lil Wayne, Swae Lee, and The Weeknd.

title: George Fest: A Night to Celebrate the Music of George Harrison [Live]
summary: The live recording of the tribute concert at the Fonda Theater in Los Angeles on September 28, 2014 featured such artists as Black Rebel Motorcycle Club, Cold War Kids, Spoon's Britt Daniel, Perry Farrell, the Flaming Lips, the Killers' Brandon Flowers, Ben Harper, Dhani Harrison, Norah Jones, Conan O'Brien, The Strokes' Nick Valensi, Heart's Ann Wilson, Brian Wilson and Weird Al Yankovic.

title: In Time to Voices
summary: The third album for the British duo was produced with Mike Crossey.

title: Women's Studies
summary: The Chicago producer/DJ's latest album of electronica features influences from a variety of genres, such as jungle and ragga, as well as the Chicago house subgenre known as juke or footwork.

title: Daydreams & Nightmares
summary: The second full-length album for the Swedish indie pop band was produced by Patrik Berger.

title: Fire Like This
summary: The second album produced by Mike Crossey for Brighton's Laura-Mary Carter and Steven Ansell was recorded on analogue tape but still retains its punk influences.

title: Wonderful Crazy Night
summary: The 33rd studio release for the British singer-songwriter was co-produced with T-Bone Burnett.

title: Computers & Blues
summary: Mike Skinner had announced this fifth album would be his last as The Streets.

title: Pajama Club
summary: Neil Finn and his new band, featuring his wife Sharon, release their debut album.

title: Le Voyage dans la Lune (A Trip to the Moon)
summary: The French duo expand on the score they created for the restoration of Georges Melies' silent short film Le Voyage dans la Lune in this full-length soundtrack.

title: Sensuous
summary: Eclectic Japanese indie-rocker Keigo Oyamada returns with his first Cornelius album in five years.
The second full-length release for the pop group formed during the second season of The X Factor features guest appearances from Missy Elliott, Fetty Wap, and Ty Dolla Sign.

title: Interiors
summary: The electronic second release for Cameron Mesirow was inspired by her move to New York.

title: Amanda Leigh
summary: The latest album for the actress/pop singer was produced with Mike Viola and on her manager's new record label.

title: The Ghost in Daylight
summary: Nick Talbot's fourth album on Warp sees the singer-songwriter moving back to a more folk-based sound.

title: Alpinisms
summary: The debut album for the band led by ex-Secret Machines member Benjamin Curtis.

title: Delirium
summary: The third full-length studio release for the British pop singer features production from Greg Kurstin, Max Martin, Ilya Salmanzadeh, and Ryan Tedder.

title: Nina Revisited: A Tribute to Nina Simone
summary: The tribute album to the High Priestess of Soul was co-executive produced by Lauryn Hill and Robert Glasper with artist such as Mary J. Blige, Common, Lalah Hathaway, Gregory Porter, Lisa Simone, Alice Smith, Jazmine Sullivan, and Usher covering her standards.

title: Dark Eyes
summary: The debut release for the Montreal indie rock band was co-produced by  Daniel Lagac and Nygel Asselin.

title: The  Lion the Beast the Beat
summary: The fourth album for the band was produced by Jim Scott and includes several tracks written by Dan Auerbach of The Black Keys.

title: Space Ducks
summary: The soundtrack to the singer-songwriter's comic book of the same name released at SXSW in 2012 features songs by Deer Tick, Eleanor Friedberger, Fruit Bats, Lavender Diamond, and Unknown Mortal Orchestra.

title: The Babies
summary: The indie rock band formed by Cassie Romone of Vivian Girls and Kevin Morby of Woods releases its debut album.

title: Temporary Pleasure
summary: The latest album for the electronic duo includes The Gossip's Beth Ditto, Hot Chip's Alexis Taylor, Super Furry Animals/Neon Neon's Gruff Rhys, Yeasayer's Chris Keating, Telepath, and Jamie Lidell as guest singers.

title: In Our Bedroom After The War
summary: The fourth album for the Canadian indie rock band.

title: Light At The End Of The World
summary: Gareth Jones produced this ten-song set from the duo of Vince Clark and Andy Bell.

title: The Garden
summary: The electro-pop duo's third album once again features vocals by Sia Furler.

title: U&I
summary: The fourth album for the electronic producer/artist who has worked with Bjork features Mt. Sims.

title: Make Do With What You Got
summary: The singer tackles songs penned by the likes of Bob Dyland and Van Morrison on this Don Was-produced disc.

title: Fever Dream
summary: The third full-length release for the Icelandic band was co-produced with Rich Costey.

title: La La Land
summary: The second album for the Canadian indie rock band was recorded in Montreal and Paris, France.

title: Himalayan
summary: The third full-length studio release for the British alternative rock trio was produced by Nick Launay.

title: Non Stop Erotik
summary: Frank Black of The Pixies releases his latest solo album coproduced with Eric Drew Feldman.

title: Passion, Pain & Demon Slayin'
summary: The sixth full-length release for the hip-hop artist features guest appearances from André Benjamin, Travis Scott, Willow Smith, and Pharrell Williams.

title: Braver Than We Are
summary: Produced by Anthrax's Paul Crook, the 13th full-length release from the singer-songwriter/actor sees the return of songs written by Jim Steinman.

title: Back on the Planet
summary: The latest release for the Los Angeles producer is an instrumental album.

title: No Need To Be Downhearted
summary: This is the third album for the English band led by brothers Alex and Tom White, who are also members of the band Brakes.

title: 24K Magic
summary: The third full-length release for the R&B singer-songwriter was produced by Shampoo Press & Curl.

title: Tonight: Franz Ferdinand
summary: The third album for the UK rock band was produced by Dan Carey.

title: Plays the Songs of Daniel Johnston
summary: After working as part of the backing band for Daniel Johnston's 2017 tour, the trio (Doug Martsch, Jason Albertini and Steve Gere) recorded an 11-song tribute album to the singer-songwriter.

title: Moonlight
summary: The third full-length release for the San Francisco-born artist was produced by Dan Auerbach.

title: Hypnotized
summary: The debut release for the side project for The Men's Nick Chiericozzi and Mark Perro was produced by Kyle Keays-Hagerman.

title: This Is All Yours

Fresh, Eric Gales, Justin Johnson, Mr. Talkbox, Musiq Soulchild, Snowbunny, October London, Kali Uchis, World-Wide-Funkdrive, Victor Wooten, Bernie Worrell, and X-Zact.

The deluxe edition includes four additional tracks featuring Eminem, Freddie Gibbs, Lil Wayne, and Piles as guests.

summary: This is the second album for the Portland, Ore. indie rockers.

title: in•ter a•li•a

summary: This is the second album for the nu-metal band out of Wales.

Included here is a new version of their hit single "Danger! High Voltage" with the White Stripes' Jack White on backing vocals.

summary: The sixth full-length album for the Canadian indie rock band was produced with Graham Lessard and Marcus Paquin.

title: Chunky Shrapnel [Live]
summary: The live release features tracks from the Australian psychedelic rock band's 2019 tour.

title: Antarctica
summary: The second full-length release for the Los Angeles trio led by Will Ivy was recorded by Steve Albini.

title: Revelations
summary: The third full-length release for the Las Vegas singer-songwriter was self-recorded and mixed.

title: Chinese Fountain
summary: This is the fifth full-length release from the self-described "beach goth" California band.

title: Sparks

title: Modern Blues
summary: The first studio release since 2011 from the band led by Mike Scott was recorded in Nashville.

title: Vol. 1

title: Knowle West Boy
summary: The British rapper's eighth album was named in part after the area he grew up in.

title: The Evening Descends
summary: The sophomore album from the Oklahoma indie rock band.

title: Deap Lips
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the collaboration between Deap Vally and The Flaming Lips' Wayne Coyne & Steven Drozd.

title: Loud Hailer
summary: The first studio release in six years for the the British guitarist was produced with Filippo Cimatti and features Rosie Bones and Carmen Vandenberg.

title: The Ridge
summary: The second full-length release for the Arcade Fire band member features Jeremy Gara on drums.

title: MG
summary: The debut full-length studio release for Depeche Mode's Martin Gore contains 16 instrumental electronic tracks.

title: Amen & Goodbye
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Brooklyn-based band features guest appearance by Suzzy Roche of The Roches and was produced by Joey Waronker.

title: Earth
summary: The debut full-length solo release for Radiohead guitarist Ed O'Brien features guest appearances by Laura Marling and Portishead's Adrian Utley.

title: Play
summary: The latest album from the Grammy-winning country singer features guests such as B.B. King, Vince Gill, Buck Owens, Steve Wariner, and Keith Urban.

title: Range Anxiety
summary: The second full-length release for the Australian rock band was produced by Jack Farley.

title: Roots & Echoes
summary: The latest album from the British band is produced by Craig Silvey (The Magic Numbers).

title: One Nation
summary: The Berlin-based duo named after the video director releases its second album.

title: Manifest!
summary: The debut full-length release from the Brooklyn indie pop band led by Samantha Urbani and Lesley Hann.

title: Everyone Is Here

title: Blueberry Boat

title: Genetic World
summary: This debut album from the French electronica trio features the Wild Colonials' Angela McCluskey on vocals on a number of tracks.

title: Planet Pit
summary: The Miami rapper's new album consists of club bangers and features collaborations with Marc Anthony and Ne-Yo.

title: It Feels So Good When I Stop
summary: The covers album also serves as a soundtrack to his novel of the same name.

title: Labyrinthes
summary: The francophone rock band from Montreal releases its third album.

title: Wolf
summary: The third full-length studio release from the Odd Future rapper features guest appearances from such artists as Erykah Badu, Hodgy Beats, Frank Ocean, Pharrell, Laetitia Sadier, and Earl Sweatshirt.

title: Mirrorwriting
summary: The debut full-length album for the British R&B singer who graduated from the same infamous Brit School as Adele and Amy Winehouse was produced with Will Bevan (aka Burial) and Royce Wood, Jr.

title: Lantern
summary: The second full-length release for the Scottish electronic producer features guest appearances from Jhené Aiko, Antony, Devaeux, Irfane, Miguel, and Ruckazoid.

title: Life And Times
summary: The ex-Husker Du singer moves away from the electronic sounds of his more recent releases and returns to the guitar stylings he played 20 years ago.

title: Falling Off The Lavender Bridge
summary: The debut album for the ex-Test Icicles member was produced by Mike Mogis.

title: Something Like a War
summary: The third full-length release for Adam Bainbridge features guest appearances from Bahamadia, Cosima, Nadia Nair, Robyn, Seinabo Sey, Samthing Soweto, and Jazmine Sullivan.

title: Acousmatic Sorcery
summary: The Chicago-based singer-songwriter's debut album is the first release from Hot Charity, an imprint of XL Recordings.

title: Human Again
summary: Producer David Kahne worked on the singer-songwriter's fifth album.

title: All Jacked Up
summary: Album number two finds the Nashville star reuniting with songwriter John Rich in an attempt to duplicate the mega-success of her debut, 'Here For The Party.'

title: Future Hndrxx Presents: The WIZRD

title: Intuit
summary: Menomena's Brent Knopf releases the first album of his solo project, Ramona Falls, which features more than 30 guests musicians.

title: Atlantis: Hymns For Disco
summary: Toronto's Kheaven Brereton returns with his third studio album of indie hip-hop mixed with a variety of other genres.

title: Pray for the Wicked

title: Shine Your Light
summary: The second release for Gabe Fulvimar was produced by Conspiracy of Owls' Bobby Harlow.

title: Dry Land is Not a Myth
summary: The debut full-length release for the Los Angeles five-piece includes influences from rock, electronic, and world music.

title: Issa Album
summary: The debut studio release for the Atlanta rapper features production from DJ Mustard, Jake One, Metro Boomin, Southside, and Zaytoven.

title: A  World Out of Time
summary: The second release in 2012 for the Portland psychedelic rock band was recorded in its entirety instead of select tracks from hours of recording sessions.

title: Busting Visions
summary: This is the second album from the Canadian indie rock band led by Broken Social Scene singer-songwriter Jason Collett.

title: Sex Therapy
summary: The fourth album for the R&B singer features such guests as Estelle, The Game, Jay-Z, Kid Cudi, and Snoop Dogg.

title: That Lucky Old Sun
summary: The ex-Beach Boys singer releases his latest solo album, which he produced himself.

title: Sob Rock
summary: The eighth full-length studio release for the pop singer-songwriter was co-produced with Don Was.

title: Let Me Come Home
summary: The second album for the Scottish indie rock band was produced by Tony Doogan.

title: Ultraviolet
summary: The debut album for the rap artist features guest appearances by David Banner, Estelle, Kanye West and Too Short. It was originally scheduled to be released as "Dream Date" in 2008.

title: Welcome the Worms
summary: The second full-length release for the Los Angeles-based band that includes sister Jennifer and Jessie Clavin was co-produced by Joe Chiccarelli and Carlos de la Garza.

title: Cope
summary: The fourth studio release for the Atlanta-based indie rock band was produced with Dan Hannon.

title: The Red Light District
