title: Junky Star
summary: Songwriter Ryan Bingham has grown tremendously on this third full-length. Barely 30 years old, his previous work showed promise but carried the excess expected of a novice. Bingham won both a Golden Globe and an Oscar for "The Weary Kind," the theme song from the film Crazy Heart. The song was produced by T-Bone Burnett, creating a partnership extended on Junky Star. Bingham and his Dead Horses--drummer Matthew Smith, bassist Elijah Ford, and guitarist Corby Schaub, prove the song was no fluke. The sound is pure Americana; these 12 lyrically sophisticated yet direct songs, reflect a host of tense, lost, desperate, individuals dreaming the same dark dream, one that suggests that we are all growing tenser with the times. Bingham has trimmed his songwriting to the bone, while learing to use metaphor and metonomy like a veteran. A former rodeo rider, he wears his influences proudly: Guthrie, Dylan, Van Zandt, Ely, Earle, Clark, and Hubbard. He begins with a sandblasted vision of America in "the Poet." Amid acoustic guitars, a lonesome harmonica ,restrained electric and bass drum, Bingham's whiskey-smoked vocal offers a lyric theme the entire album turns on: "As I keep walking, people keep talking/About things they've never seen or done/Homeless sleep in the park, lovers kiss in the dark/Me, I keep moving on through time." Time is suspended as  Bingham's protagonists tell stories from the road (some of them bone-chilling), from America's past and present, physically and psychologically. Rootlessness as peace of mind is portrayed via country rock in "The Wandering," but the feeling in "Strange Feeling In The Air," the title track, a deeply moving acoustic murder ballad (they are strewn throughout the album), and the angry uptempo "Depression," reflect a contradiction: constant movement is the key to survival, not necessarily peace. "Hallelujah" is another murder ballad with a disturbing twist. "Lay My Head On The Rail," is pure folk poetry illustrated by a lone acoustic guitar. The blues in  "Hard Worn Trail," are rooted in poverty worry, strained,  broken relationships resulting in the search for comfort. It doesn't come anywehre on Junky Star. "All Choked Up Again," set to Waylon Jennings' brand of outlaw country closes it out by mining the existential darkness deeper. Bingham is unflinching, but his songs hold out for a glimmer of something else. The only real consolation Junky Star offers is that no one need feel alone in her or his desperation-this is a true accomplishment. Bingham has delivered a set of songs that mirrors our uncertain times in a musical language that doesn't unduly distort or romanticise them. ~ Thom Jurek

title: Disconnect from Desire
summary: On their second album, School of Seven Bells cast themselves as an update of a specific kind of misfit band. Alpinisms reconstituted late-â€™80/early-â€˜90s shoegaze. Disconnect from Desire, however, updates the sound of a kind of band that would have opened for Peter Gabriel and Eurythmics, or headlined over Revolver, rather than tour with the likes of Lush, Ride, and Pale Saints. Here, a focused songcraft and central placement of the Deheza twinsâ€™ alluring vocals -- which tend to be lower and more earthly than they were on the debut -- disallow School of Seven Bells from being squarely shoegaze. At the same time, the band is too left of center, too odd, to be considered anywhere near the mainstream. Their cleaner, less wispy, more muscular sound, combined with more traditional songwriting, is not that radical a change. Itâ€™s closer to a slight shift that registers after a couple spins, once it becomes apparent that deeply emotive and relatively sparse songs like â€œI L U,â€ â€œJoviann,â€ and â€œThe Waitâ€ would have made excellent tracks buried throughout Sireâ€™s Just Say series. They have shoegaze lyric-generator staples like wind, waves, ocean, storms, and even talk of â€œslipping away.â€ And yet, the words are not merely functional, written solely for the sake of complementing the sound as an additional instrument. Theyâ€™re either poetically vague or vaguely poetic -- stuff like â€œLet me will the dial to turn and gild the air with silver pearls of rainâ€ and â€œWhenâ€™s the wait a cradle in which youâ€™re lulled from time to time, soundly spun into an insensate lie.â€ The thicker, more driving songs resemble a polished, warm Curve, whipping up squalls of noise over robust played-and-programmed rhythms that soar more often than batter. No matter the amount of layering, not a single element is obscured. This vivid directness suits them very well. ~ Andy Kellman

title: Let It Be... Naked
summary: Originally intended as a loose, spontaneous recording called 'Get Back,' 'Let It Be' was eventually released (after the band's breakup) after being shelved and then reproduced/enhanced by Phil Spector, leaving many fans (and an angry Paul McCartney) wondering, "what if?" title: Come And Get It!
summary: Ever since the dawn of the electric guitar, white boys have sung the blues, some with considerably more success than others. Eli â€œPaperboyâ€ Reed is part of that long tradition, but he stands apart from the pack as much as he belongs to it, due in large part to his age. Raised on CD reissues of classic blues and soul -- he was not even 10 when the first Complete Stax/Volt Singles box came out -- Reed has absorbed the sound and sensibility of classic â€˜60s soul but sings without any white-boy blues affectations, totally comfortable in his own skin because nobody else his age, of any race, was attempting to make this kind of music. This can cause a kind of a disconnect -- Reed sounds so white when he sings, itâ€™s disarming -- but he pours on the passion and has fully absorbed the tight turns of Stax and loves the sound as much as the structure, so much so that Come and Get It -- his third LP and first for a major label -- feels a bit like an unearthed relic, built on songs and sounds that could pass for unheard gems if it wasnâ€™t for Reedâ€™s unapologetically white voice, free of affectations and ticks. Some of that may be due to producer Mike Elizondoâ€™s work -- he manages to make this sound like a throwback without being stiff, and without having a hint of Mark Ronsonâ€™s hipster retroism for Amy Winehouse -- but heâ€™s just articulating Reedâ€™s gifts, letting the songs stand front and center. And thatâ€™s whatâ€™s remarkable about Come and Get It: this is not a modern-day blues album, itâ€™s a classic soul album, with almost all the tracks clocking in at 3:30 or less, leaving very little room for showboating solos. All concentration is on the tunes themselves, with the band kicking them toward kineticism, Reed channeling all his energy into making the songs sing, and they wind up sticking, sounding a bit like forgotten classics upon first listen, then winding up as familiar favorites upon the second. If there is any fault here, itâ€™s that Reedâ€™s voice remains perennially boyish, sometimes preventing this from achieving a level of gravity, but thereâ€™s no attempt to hide this: itâ€™s an honest reflection of who Reed is, a young kid from Boston in love with the Southern sounds of the â€˜60s and intent on carrying them on, even if he invites ridicule or scorn. He believes it, man, and based on Come and Get It, itâ€™s hard not to believe it too. ~ Stephen Thomas Erlewine

title: Trigga
summary: The sixth full-length studio release album for the R&B singer features guest appearances from Justin Bieber, Juicy J, Mila J, Nicki Minaj, and Ty Dolla $ign.

But although the Aussies did indeed get their start as a Nirvana cover band, there is a bit more to their debut album 'Highly Evolved' than Grunge, Part 2.

title: Fold Your Hands Child, You Walk Like A Peasant
Animator

title: Underwater Cinematographer
summary: This is the debut for the Toronto six-piece led by Adrian Jewett.

title: Believe

title: Hands
summary: The debut album for the singer-songwriter was produced with Greg Kurstin and Joe Goddard.

title: Aimlessness
summary: The fourth release for Jimmy Tamborello as Dntel includes guest vocals from Will Wiesenfeld (also known as Baths) and Nite Jewel.

title: Songs Of Mass Destruction
summary: Glen Ballard produces the ex-Eurythmics singer's fourth album.

title: EVOL

title: Cotillions
summary: The second full-length solo release for The Smashing Pumpkins lead singer under his full name was recorded in Chicago and Nashville.

title: The Laughing Apple

title: Ratworld
summary: The debut full-length release for the indie duo of Ryan Needham and Liza Violet was produced by MJ of Hookworms.

title: Peanut Butter And Jelly Live At The Ginger Minge
summary: This is the third studio album (don't believe the title) for the San Francisco punkers.

title: Von

title: Terrible Human Beings
summary: The third full-length release for the Chicago-area garage rock band was produced by Jim Abbiss.

title: Subtitulo
summary: The Nebraskan singer-songwriter recorded this seventh album in his new home of Spain.

title: Skilled Mechanics
summary: The debut release for Tricky's side project features guest appearances from Francesca Belmonte, Ivy, DJ Milo, Oh Land, and Xdare.

title: Diamond Hoo Ha
summary: The sixth studio album for the English rock quartet was recorded in Germany.

title: Major General
summary: The debut solo album for The Hold Steady's Franz Nicolay.

title: Amnesty (I)
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Canadian experimental electronic band is its first with new singer Edith Frances.

title: I Am Not a Human Being
summary: With Southern sounds, spacey themes, and smooth rhymes, the rapper returns from incarceration with his latest release of hip-hop hits.

title: Riot!
summary: Hayley Williams leads her Franklin, Tennessee-based band in their second album.

title: Dunes
summary: Produced by Tim Goldsworthy, the second full-length release for the Santa Barbara indie band was inspired by Lake Michigan.

title: In Another World
summary: The 20th full-length studio release for the rock band was produced with Julian Raymond.

title: Amelita
summary: Jim Scott returns as producer on the second release from the Dixie Chicks' Emily Robison and Martie Maguire as the Court Yard Hounds.

title: Nothing to Do

title: Dirty Work
summary: This is the emo-pop band's major-label debut.

title: Green Language
summary: The second full-length release for the Scottish electronic producer features guest appearances from Danny Brown, D Double E, and Gorgeous Children.

title: Hot Cakes
summary: The British glam/hard rock band returns to record and produce its third album after a five year absence.

title: My Everything
summary: The R&B singer's first studio album since 1994 includes a duet with Babyface.

title: Educated Guess
summary: The singer-songwriter's latest is a solo release in every sense of the word, as DiFranco wrote, produced, played, and sang everything on the album (not to mention releasing it on her own record label).

title: The Datsuns
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the New Zealand rockers, who have drawn comparisons to everyone from The Stooges and AC/DC to, of course, the White Stripes, and have been the subject of fawning articles in the UK music press (but then again, who hasn't) in recent months.

title: Lucky 7

title: Walls
summary: The second full-length album for the Australian duo was produced by Howard Redekopp.

summary: The fifth full-length release for the San Francisco garage/psych rock quartet was partially influenced by Tim Cohen's stay in Arizona.

title: Gameshow
summary: The third full-length release from the Northern Ireland indie rock band was produced by Jackknife Lee.

title: All Hail Bright Futures
artist: And So I Watch You from Afar
summary: The third full-length release for the rock band from Belfast was produced by Rocky O'Reilly.

title: The Element Of Freedom
summary: The Grammy-winning singer-songwriter releases her fourth studio album.

title: Back & Fourth
summary: Mike Mogis produced the singer-songwriter's first album in three years.

title: Golden Pollen
summary: This latest release for Scott Herren's Catalan- and tropicalia-themed Prefuse 73 side project is basically a Herren solo record, with the producer even singing on a number of tracks. Other vocalists include Mia Doi Todd and Jose Gonzalez.

summary: Ken Stringfellow and Jon Auer reunite for their first album as The Posies in seven years. They are joined by Matt Harris (Oranger) on bass and Darren Minwalla (Preston School of Industry) on drums.

title: It's a Corporate World
summary: The Detroit duo of Joshua Epstein and Daniel Zott release another album of psychedelic indie pop.

title: Mugiboogie
summary: This is the third album for the Icelandic artist.

title: Belladonna of Sadness
summary: The debut full-length release for the Los Angeles-based singer-songwriter was produced by James Ford and Alex Turner.

title: Bones
summary: This is the fourth full-length release for the Brooklyn trio led by Ryan Lott.

title: Bruiser
summary: The third album for the British indie rock band was produced by Andrew Scheps.

title: The Most Incredible Thing
summary: This is the soundtrack for the ballet based on a Hans Christian Anderson story.

title: Howl
summary: Produced by Howard Bilerman, the third full-length release for the Chicago R&B/soul band introduces rock and pop sounds.

title: Imposter
summary: The third full-length release for the collaboration between Dave Gahan and Soulsavers is a rock covers.

title: Ivywild
summary: The second full-length release for the music project of Winston Yellen features influences from R&B and electronic pop.

title: I Thought the Future Would Be Cooler
summary: The sixth full-length release for the now Los Angeles-based electro-pop duo was produced by Jona Bechtolt and Rob Kieswetter.

title: Acoustic at the Ryman [Live]
summary: The ten-track live acoustic release from the indie rock band features songs recorded at Nashville's Ryman Auditorium in April 2013.

title: The Slideshow Effect
summary: This is the debut full-length album on Sub Pop for the Canadian dream pop duo.

title: Recordings Of Music For Film

title: Music to Make Love to Your Old Lady By
summary: "Nathaniel Merriweather" is merely the latest incarnation of producer Dan "The Automator" Nakamura, best known for his work with Dr. Octagon and the Gorillaz. Merriweather was last seen on 1999's Handsome Boy Modeling School debut, and here he is joined in his new band, Lovage, by Kid Koala, Damon Albarn, Prince Paul, Faith No More's Mike Patton, and the Elysian Fields' Jennifer Charles, among others.

title: Time Bomb
summary: The sophomore effort from the Los Angeles rockers.

title: God Bless The Blake Babies
summary: Juliana Hatfield and company reunite for their first album in 8 years.

title: Right On!
summary: The debut full-length solo release for the bassist of Warpaint was co-produced with Norm Block.

title: Wait 'Til Night
summary: The second full-length release for the British dance artist features influences of R&B, reggae, and synthpop.

title: Surfing
summary: Devendra Banhart and Priestbird's Greg Rogove join up to release their debut album.

title: Forever Hasn't Happened Yet
summary: The X frontman's fifth solo disc features guests Neko Case, Grant-Lee Phillips, Dave Alvin and Kristin Hersh.

title: Learn To Live
summary: The Hootie & the Blowfish singer's sophomore solo album was produced by Frank Rogers.

title: The  Mountain Will Fall
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the DJ/producer features guest appearances from Bleep Bloop, Nils Frahm, Ernie Fresh, Matthew Halsall, G Jones, and Run the Jewels.

title: Joyride
summary: Originally announced in 2015, the second full-length studio release for the R&B artist features guest appearances from French Montana, Future, Little Dragon, Offset, and Ty Dolla $ign is finally out.

title: Taiga
summary: The fifth full-length release for singer-songwriter Nika Roza Danilova was co-produced with Dean Hurley.

title: Blood From A Stone
summary: The latest album for the Norwegian singer-songwriter.

title: Go Go Smear The Poison Ivy
summary: The Icelandic group releases their fourth album.

title: Hot Fuss
summary: 'Hot Fuss' marks the debut for the Las Vegas-based garage rockers led by 22-year old vocalist/songwriter Brandon Flowers.

title: Dos
summary: The second full-length studio album for the quartet from San Francisco.

title: Hopeless Fountain Kingdom
summary: The second full-length release for the alternative pop artist features guest appearances from Cashmere Cat, Fifth Harmony's Lauren Jauregui and Migos' Quavo.

title: The State vs. Radric Davis
summary: The second album for the Alabama-born rapper features such guest artists as Lil Wayne, Jadakiss, Piles, Rick Ross, Soulja Boy Tell 'Em, and Usher.

summary: The Canadian DJ who is known for his mouse-head costume releases his third full-length album.

title: Breakthrough
summary: The debut full-length release for William Bensussen as The Gaslamp Killer features guest appearances from such artist as Gonjasufi, Shigeto, Samiyam, Miguel Atwood-Ferguson, and Daedelus.

summary: The fourth full-length release for the British singer-songwriter was recorded in Nashville and features guest appearances from Dan Auerbach (on guitar) and Noah Cyrus.

title: Never Never Land

Guests this time out include Josh Homme (Queens Of The Stone Age), Robert "3D" del Naja (Massive Attack), Brian Eno, Ian Brown (Stone Roses), Mani (Stone Roses/Primal Scream) Joel Cadbury (South) and Jarvis Cocker (Pulp).

title: The DEFinition
summary: The rapper's eleventh album includes six tracks produced by Timbaland. R. Kelly also guests.

title: Sacred Love
summary: Did you know this guy used to be in the Police?

title: Say You Will

title: Open
summary: The first album of new material in three years for the ever-consistent Cowboy Junkies.

title: Two Vines
summary: The third full-length release for the Australian electronic duo was produced with Peter Mayes and Jonathan Sloan.

title: Mentor Tormentor
summary: The Los Angeles band's follow-up to their 2004 release, Treble & Tremble.

title: Lifeblood
summary: The Welsh band's seventh studio disc was produced by Tony Visconti and Greg Haver.

title: Magpie and the Dandelion

title: A Thousand Suns

title: Kiss Me Once
summary: The Australian pop singer worked with Enrique Iglesias, Greg Kurstin, MNEK, Ariel Rechtshaid, Sia, and Pharrell Williams on her 12th studio release.

title: Xscape
summary: The posthumously released eight-track album from the pop singer features unreleased songs completed between 1983 and 1999 with new production from executive producer L.A. Reid, as well as Jerome "J-Roc" Harmon, Rodney Jerkins, John McClain, StarGate, and Timbaland. A deluxe edition includes a disc of songs without the current producers input.

title: Get the Money
summary: The third full-length release for the Foo Fighters drummer with the Coattail Riders features guest appearances from Dave Grohl, Chrissie Hynde, Perry Farrell, Duff McKagan, LeAnn Rimes, Roger Taylor, Joe Walsh, and Nancy Wilson.

title: Arrows
summary: The second full-length release for the British indie-pop singer was written in  Berlin, England (London & Norfolk), and France.

title: Shapes & Shadows
summary: Gomez guitarist Ben ottewell releases his debut solo album produced by Will Golden.

title: Seeing Eye Dog
summary: The band fronted by Page Hamilton includes yet another new line-up for its seventh studio album.

title: Exquisite Corpse
summary: The fourth album for the Los Angeles-based electronica producer finds him joined by guests MF Doom, Mike Ladd and Prefuse 73.

title: Everything Now
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the Canadian indie rock band was co-produced with Daft Punk's Thomas Bangalter, Portishead's Geoff Barrow, Markus Dravs, and Pulp's Steve Mackey.

title: Fatherland
summary: The third full-length solo release for the Bloc Party lead singer (though the first under his full name) features guest appearances from Olly Alexander and Corinne Bailey Rae.

title: Film School
summary: The San Francisco post-punk band's second album follows five years after their debut.

title: Sundark and Riverlight

title: Music For Listening To Music To
summary: The fourth full-length release for the indie rock band was produced by Ryan Adams.

title: Ready to Die
summary: The first studio release since 1973's Raw Power to be credited under Iggy & The Stooges, reunites Iggy Pop with James Williamson, Scott  Asheton, and new bassist Mike Watt (Ron Asheton passed away in 2009) for the band's fifth studio album.

title: Total
summary: The French electro and house music producer/remixer releases a debut full-length album.

title: Eskmo
summary: Brendan Angelides releases his debut full-length album as Eskmo.

title: A Time To Love
summary: The legendary singer's first album in ten years combines R&B, soul and hip-hop. Guests include Paul McCartney, Prince and India.Arie.

title: MTV Unplugged [Live]
summary: The latest MTV Unplugged release is from Florence + the Machine and it includes a cover of Jackson with Josh Homme.

title: American Goldwing
summary: The Portland folk-rockers return with a new album of psychedelic roots music.

title: Still Not Getting Any
summary: Bob Rock (Metallica) produced this sophomore album for the Montreal-based pop-punk band.

title: The Massacre
summary: The rapper's second album was "executive" produced by Dr. Dre, Eminem and 50 himself and includes the singles "Piggybank" and "Disco Inferno."

title: Everything Goes Wrong
summary: This is the second album for the Brooklyn-based indie rock trio.

title: Just Like You
summary: The top female finisher on the eighth season of American Idol releases her debut album.

title: The Hunger For More
summary: This is the solo debut for Banks, a member of G Unit.

title: Kamikaze
summary: The Chicago rapper's long-awaited follow-up to 'Adrenaline Rush' features contributions from Kanye West, Toxic, Cee-Lo and R. Kelly.

title: Leave Your Name

title: The Phoenix Album

title: Reptile
summary: This new 14-track set from Eric Clapton features a mix of originals and covers (including songs by Stevie Wonder and James Taylor).

title: Inside Llewyn Davis [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]

title: Raven in the Grave

title: A Crow Left Of The Murder

title: Let Me Introduce My Friends

title: Dear Miss Lonelyhearts
summary: The fourth release for the California indie rock band is its first with former Modest Mouse and Murder City Devils guitarist Dann Gallucci, who also co-produced the album with Lars Stalfors.

title: Ode To J. Smith
summary: The sixth album for the Scottish rock band was produced by Emery Dobyns.

title: Free Yourself Up
summary: The sixth full-length release for the Boston band was recorded in Nashville with Dan Knobler.

title: Heartache City
summary: The sixth full-length release for the duo of Sierra and Bianca Casady was recorded in the south of France.

title: A Picture Of The Three Of Us At The Gate To The Garden Of Eden
summary: The debut album for the Washington, DC-based indie rock band.

title: Manhattan
summary: The debut full-length release for the New York punk rock band was produced by John Hill.

title: In Waves
summary: The Floridian heavy metal band releases their fifth studio album.

title: Face The Promise
summary: The 61-year-old rocker returns with his first new album in 11 years.

title: Richer Than I Ever Been
summary: The latest full-length studio release for rapper Rick Ross features guest appearances from 21 Savage, Yungeen Ace, Benny The Butcher, Blxst, DreamDoll, Willie Falcon, Future, Wiz Khalifa, Major Nine, Jazmine Sullivan, The-Dream, and Wale.

title: The Beautiful Struggle
summary: The literary rapper's second LP features production by the usual suspects (Kanye West, The Neptunes, Just Blaze). Mary J Blige guests.

title: Outside
summary: The indie rock band from Minnesota self-produced its third album.

title: Brass
summary: The fourth studio release for the Knoxville, Tennessee indie rock band was produced by Patrick Carney of the Black Keys.

title: My Head Is an Animal
summary: This is the debut full-length album for the Icelandic folk rock band that won the Músiktilraunir, their homeland's battle of the bands competition, in 2010.

title: Guerolito
summary: Beck's latest LP, 'Guero,' is remixed track-for-track by the likes of Air, Boards Of Canada, El-P and Subtle.

title: Country Mile
summary: After a two-year acting stint at The Globe and in the West End, the British singer/actor returns with a self-produced album of Americana.

title: Hymns
summary: This is the first album in nearly 20 years since Richard Davies and Eric Matthews released their debut albums as Cardinal in 1994.

title: Weird!
summary: The second full-length release for the British alternative pop artist features contributions from Travis Barker, Machine Gun Kelly, and Dan Reynolds.

title: Racy
summary: The second full-length release for the indie rockers was produced by Chris Coady.

title: G is For Deep
summary: The latest solo album for Anticon co-founder Adam Drucker is his first official studio release.

title: People and Things
summary: This is the third album for the rock band led by the former Something Corporate singer Andrew McMahon.

title: Ask The Night
summary: This is Orenda Fink's second solo album, after stints with the bands Art In Manila and O+S.

title: Is And Always Was
summary: Jason Falkner produced the latest album for the Texas-based artist.

title: The Airborne Toxic Event
summary: This is the debut album for the Southern California rock quintet.

title: Venus
summary: The first solo release for the singer-songwriter since the break-up of  The Civil Wars was co-produced with Matt Morris.

title: Pale Fire
summary: This is the fourth full-length studio release for the Sweden's Sarah Assbring as El Perro Del Mar.

title: Mo Beauty
summary: The Clap Your Hands Say Yeah's frontman releases his debut solo album produced by Steve Berlin.

title: I Look To You
summary: The multi-award winning singer returns to release her first album in seven years.

title: Two Lanes of Freedom
summary: The 12th studio release for the country singer is his first on the Big Machine label and it includes guest appearances from Taylor Swift and Keith Urban.

title: Per Second, Per Second, Per Second... Every Second
summary: The Massachusetts-based trio's fourth album is their first for a major label. Dave Fridmann produces.

title: Rock'n'Roll
summary: Recorded in just two weeks after Adams (rather, his record company) scrapped plans to release 'Love Is Hell' as his official follow-up to 'Gold' (the former will instead appear as a 2-part EP), 'Rock'n'Roll' features guest appearances from Billie Joe Armstrong (Green Day), Melissa Auf Der Mauer (Hole) and Parker Posey (every indie film in the last 15 years).

title: Notes And The Like
summary: This is the second full-length for the German indie-electro-pop duo of Stephanie Bohm (also in Couch) and The Notwist's Micha Acher.

title: Winchester Cathedral
summary: The distinctive Liverpool-based band returns with a third studio LP.

title: Beast Moans
summary: 'Beast' marks the debut for Swan Lake, the new collaboration between Destroyer's Dan Bejar, Wolf Parade's Spencer Krug and Frog Eyes' Carey Mercer.

title: Southern Voice
summary: The latest album for the actor/country singer from Louisiana features a song co-written by Brett James and Nickelback's Chad Kroeger.

title: Everywhere At Once
summary: The San Francisco Bay Area native releases his third album, his first on Epitaph Records.

title: White Women
summary: The fourth release for the Canadian electronic duo features guest appearances from Ezra Koenig, Solange and Toro Y Moi.

title: Love & Evol
summary: The latest full-length release from the Japanese noise-rock group is its first on the Third Man label.

title: Girl
summary: The second full-length Columbia Nashville release for the country singer-songwriter features guest appearances from Brothers Osborne and Brandi Carlile.

title: Callus
summary: The third full-length release for the California artist was self-produced and features contributions from the Cure's Pearl Thompson.

title: World of Joy
summary: Produced by Chris Heidman, the second full-length release for the Minneapolis rock band is its first with new drummer Rory MacMurdo.

title: Leave No Trace
summary: The sophomore album from the Los Angeles quintet fuses Afropop with '80s new wave.

title: Dig Out Your Soul
summary: The British rock band releases its seventh album, produced by Dave Sardy.

title: The Bravery
summary: Another hot, retro-sounding band based in New York? Is there some sort of factory churning these bands out? (Or in the case of The Bravery, a Factory?) The band's self-titled debut, preceded by the requisite buzz, utilizes a new wave-flavored sound which is also reminiscent of, oh, let's just say New Order and The Cure.

title: As I Am
summary: Alicia Keys' third album includes guest vocalists Marsha Ambrosius, John Mayer, and Linda Perry.

title: Stones
summary: The four-track release from Mats Gustafsson and Colin Stetson was recorded live at the Vancouver Jazz Festival in 2011.

title: Everybody
summary: This is the foruth album for the New York-based singer-songwriter.

title: From This Moment On
summary: The Canadian singer/pianist tackles American standards, backed by a big band on most of the tracks.

title: Chase This Light
summary: Butch Vig produces their sixth studio album.

title: Joy
summary: The second collaborative album by Ty Segall and White Fence features 15 tracks that range from 16 seconds to over five minutes long.

title: This is PiL
summary: This is the first album in 20 years for the band led by the Sex Pistol's John Lydon. The line-up includes Bruce Smith, Lu Edmonds, and Scott Firth.

title: Come of Age
summary: This second album for the London quartet was produced by Ethan Johns and recorded at ICP Studios in Brussels, Belgium and the Distillery in Bath, England.

title: Year In The Kingdom
summary: The sixth solo album for the Fleet Foxes member is his second album for the year.

title: The Only Place
summary: Produced by Jon Brion, the second album for Best Coast is its first since drummer Ali Koehler was let go by the indie pop duo.

title: Jet Black
summary: The second release on Arts & Letters for the Canadian singer, who also appeared in John Cameron Mitchell's movie Shortbus.

title: Good Graces
summary: The third solo release for the singer-songwriter features guest vocals from frequent collaborator, Jenny Lewis.

title: Trespassing
summary: The sophomore release for Adam Lambert features production and co-written songs by Nikka Costa, Dr. Luke, Claude Kelly, Bruno Mars, Sam Sparro, and Pharrell Williams.

title: Build with Erosion
summary: The band formed by drummers Shane Aspegren and Lori Sean Berg releases its third album recorded in Paris, France, with Antoine Gaillet.

title: Jesus Piece
summary: The fifth studio release for California rapper The Game features guest appearances from such artists as 2 Chainz, Big Sean, Chris Brown, J. Cole, Common, Jamie Foxx, Kendrick Lamar, Lil Wayne, Rick Ross, Tyga, Kanye West, and  Wiz Khalifa.

title: Pedestrian
summary: This is the second full-length solo release for the former Yuck frontman.

title: Earth Junk
summary: Neil Michael Hagerty's latest band releases its sixth album, which is only 33 minutes long.

title: The Cover Up
artist: I Am The World Trade Center
summary: The 80s-influenced laptop-pop duo of Dan Geller and Amy Dykes return with their third LP.

title: Waves Are Universal
summary: The current Mojave 3 and former Slowdive member makes her long-awaited solo debut with 'Waves Are Universal,' which features production by David Naughton and drumming by Ashley Bates (Chapterhouse).

title: Fulfilled/Complete
summary: This is the second solo disc for Faint bassist Joel Petersen. Mike Mogis produces.

title: Pole

title: From the Cradle to the Rave
summary: Full of futuristic synthesizer sounds and analog arrangements, Irish-born Marcus Lambkin's album of house jams features guest vocals from Hot Chip and LCD Soundsystem.

title: The Naked Truth
summary: The soon-to-be-incarcerated (for perjury) rapper offers a fourth solo disc. Kanye West and Scott Storch are among the producers.

title: Wash the Sins Not Only the Face
summary: This is the second full-length release from the Brighton indie rock trio.

title: 100 Miles from Memphis
summary: Sheryl Crow's seventh album takes a soulful musical direction for the singer-songwriter and features guest appearances from Justin Timberlake and Keith Richards.

title: Up From Below
summary: This is the debut album for the 11-piece indie rock band led by Alex Ebert.

title: BRVNX (V)
summary: The fifth full-length (non-Mariachi) release for the Los Angels punk band was produced by Rob Schnapf.

title: Youth Authority
summary: The first new studio release in six years for the pop-punk band led by Joel and Benji Madden was produced by John Feldmann and features guest appearances from Sleeping With Sirens's Kellin Quinn and Biffy Clyro's Simon Neil.

title: Between the Walls
summary: The third release for the experimental rock side-project that included Spiritualized's John Coxon, Hot Chip's Alexis Taylor, and Pat Thomas, is the last with This Heat's Charles Hayward.

title: Never Trust a Happy Song
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the Los Angeles-based indie rock quintet.

title: Rain Machine
summary: Kyp Malone who has appeared on TV On The Radio and Iran's albums, releases his debut solo album.

title: Crayons
summary: The first album of new songs in over 15 years from the queen of disco.

title: The Capitol Studios Sessions
summary: Recorded live in studio with an audience, the debut full-length release for the actor/jazz pianist with his band, The Mildred Snitzer Orchestra and features guest appearances from Till Bronner, Imelda May, Haley Reinhart, and Sarah Silverman.

title: Icky Blossoms
summary: The debut album for the indie pop trio was produced by Dave Sitek.

title: Say It
summary: The Canadian indie rock trio releases the follow-up to the band's 2008 debut, Red, Yellow & Blue.

title: In Dream
summary: The fifth full-length release for the British indie rock band was self-produced and features a guest appearance from Rachel Goswell of Slowdive.

title: Here Comes Science
summary: This is the latest children's album for the band and as suggested by the title, it focuses on science.

title: The Spinning Top
summary: Blur's Graham Coxon releases his seventh solo album, produced by Stephen Street.

title: Adventures In The Underground Journey To The Stars
summary: The London-based trio of Joel Cadbury, Jamie McDonald and Brett Shaw return with a third album that finds them relying less on electronica elements than previous efforts.

title: Jackrabbit
summary: The second full-length release for the Brooklyn chamber pop band led by Ellis Ludwig-Leone features vocals from Allen Tate and Charlene Kaye.

title: Collegrove
summary: The collaboration with Lil Wayne (due to contract issues was listed as a 2 Chainz album) includes two tracks from the earlier released mixtape Felt Like Cappin.

title: The Charm
summary: The Ying Yang Twins guest on the Southern rapper's first release for Big Boi's Purple Ribbon label.

title: Red Bedroom
summary: The New York City five-piece (yes, they're one of *those* New York bands) make their debut with 'Red Bedroom,' mixing dance and punk like it's 2002 all over again.

title: Triple F Life: Friends, Fans and Family
summary: The second full-length studio album from Waka Flocka Flame features guest appearances from such artists as B.o.B., Drake, Flo Rider, Ludacris, Nicki Minaj, and Trey Songz.

title: Anthems
summary: This is the debut release from the rock band formed by former Gallows singer Frank Carter and Hope Conspiracy guitarist Jim Carroll.

title: The  Blackbird Diaries
summary: The Eurythmics member releases a solo album of rock and blues, recorded at Nashville's famous Blackbird Studios.

title: Join With Us
summary: The sophomore album for the Sussex, England pop rock band.

title: Cavalier Youth
summary: The fourth full-length release for the British rock band led by Josh Franceschi was produced by Neal Avron.

title: Not Animal
artist: Margot & the Nuclear So and So's
summary: The second album for the group is its first on the Epic label. A vinyl version named Animal! contains songs they preferred, whereas this album contains songs preferred by Epic.

title: For Ever
summary: The second full-length release for the British soul collective was recorded in London and Los Angeles.

title: Just Tell Me That You Want Me: A Tribute To Fleetwood Mac
summary: Produced by Randall Poster and Gelya Robb, the 17 track tribute album includes such artists as Lee Ranaldo, J Mascis, Best Coast, New Pornographers, Marianne Faithfull, Lykke Li, Bonnie Prince Billy, Washed Out, Tame Impala, Craig Wedren, St. Vincent, The Kills, Gardens & Villa, The Crystal Ark, and MGMT covering Fleetwood Mac songs.

title: If The Ocean Gets Rough

summary: The sixth full-length studio release for the Los Angeles alternative rock trio was written in Santa Cruz and includes a cover of The Call's "Let The Day Begin." [Michael Been, the father of lead singer Robert, fronted The Call and passed away in 2010.]

summary: Often compared to Pavement and the Buzzcocks, the London-based quartet release its first full-length debut of lo-fi rock.

title: The Constant
summary: Elvis Baskette produces the fourth album for the St. Louis rock band that started out as Big Blue Monkey (an existing blues group by the same name resulted in a name change).

title: The  Paradigm Shift
summary: The 11th studio release for the nu-metal band is the first with guitarist Brian "Head" Welch since 2003's Take A Look In The Mirror.

title: Adam Ant Is the BlueBlack Hussar In Marrying The Gunner's Daughter
summary: The first studio release in 17 years for the British pop singer was produced with Boz Boorer.

title: Declaration Of Dependence
summary: The third album for the Norwegian rock duo is its first since 2004's "Riot On An Empty Street."

title: Santi
summary: This is the second LP for the Chicago emo band.

title: Otto Spooky
summary: This is album number 19 for Scotland's resident oddball Nick Currie.

title: Treble & Tremble
summary: This fourth LP for the Los Angeles indie rockers were produced by Jim Fairchild (Grandaddy) and the band's own Aaron Espinoza. The album is dedicated to (and frequently about) the late Elliott Smith, who was Espinoza's neighbor.

title: Made in the A.M.
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the boy band is its first without Zayn Malik, who left the group in March 2015.

title: All We Need
summary: The debut full-length release for the Atlanta-based artist features guest appearances from Big K.R.I.T. and Tom Morello.

title: Wait For Me
summary: Influenced by a talk he heard by David Lynch, Moby recorded the album at home.

title: Moondagger
summary: This is the latest album for Randolph Chabot, who had a track on his label's "Adult Swim" album "Ghostly Swim."

title: In A Perfect World...
summary: The long-delayed debut album for Keri Hilson features Timbaland, Lil Wayne, Keyshia Cole, Ne-Yo, T-Pain, Akon, Lil Jon, and Trina as guest artists.

title: Liberation
summary: The Washington, D.C. band's seventh album finds the band in a more political mood, even sampling President Bush (the newer one) on one track.

title: Delirium Cordia
summary: Mike Patton (Faith No More) returns for his third studio album (which consists of a single, 74-minute song!) with his more experimental outfit Fantomas.

title: Sean-Nós Nua
summary: The mercurial singer-songwriter returns with an album of interpretations of 13 traditional Irish songs.

title: Celebrity
summary: This is the third album for Justin Timberlake & co. But will it be the last?

title: It's Like This
summary: Much like her 1991 release 'Pop Pop,' this album showcases Jones' vocal talents as she reinterprets an eclectic variety of songs (by everyone from The Beatles and Marvin Gaye to Steely Dan and Gershwin) in her own unique style.

title: Just Us
summary: The 11th studio release from the German Krautrock band is said to be an invitation for fans to use the music as " a base on which to build their own music."

title: Soul Punk
summary: The Fall Out Boy singer also wrote and produced this entire debut solo album.

title: Let It Be You
summary: The debut full-length release for the collaboration between Joan As Policewoman & Benjamin Lazar Davis is loosely inspired by the musical patterns of the Central African Republic Pygmies.

title: R.Y.C.
summary: The second full-length release for the electronic producer features guest appearances from Clairo, Georgia, Ned Green, Ellie Rowsell, slowthai, Tirzah, and Wolf Alice.

title: Duets: Re-Working the Catalogue
summary: Produced with Don Was and Bob Rock, the album from the Hall of Fame artist features new arrangements of some of his less well known songs as duets with George Benson, Michael Bublé, Natalie Cole, Chris Farlowe, Georgie Fame, Mick Hucknall, Mark Knopfler, Taj Mahal, daughter Shania Morrison, Gregory Porter, P.J. Proby, Mavis Staples, Joss Stone, Clare Teal, Steve Winwood, and Bobby Womack.

title: S-M 2: Abyss in B Minor
summary: The Norwegian band recorded some of this second full-length album in a cave.

title: Yeah Right
summary: The Philadelphia indie pop band Reading Rainbow returns with a new name and two new members: Greg Frantz and Al Creedon.

title: Sleep Forever
summary: The sophomore album for the Brooklyn rock band is their first on Frenchkiss Records.

title: The Beekeeper
summary: The singer-songwriter returns with her first album of original material in three years, a conceptual work centering on the title character, with its 19 songs divided into six thematic "gardens." Damien Rice guests on one track.

title: Await Barbarians
summary: This is the second full-length solo release for the Hot Chip singer/guitarist.

title: Sawdust
summary: The collection of b-sides and remixes also features Lou Reed on one track.

title: The Journey Man
summary: The latest release for the British drum and bass artist features a guest appearance from José James.

title: Mylo Xyloto
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the alternative rock band is a concept album about the love story of Mylo Xyloto, set in an alien dystopia.

title: Talk About Body
summary: After four years of being a Brooklyn-based band, the art/music collective formed by Le Tigre's J.D. Samson finally release their debut album of disco punk with a socio-political message.

title: Spirit
summary: The season three "The X Factor" winner's first album debuted as the number one album in the UK.

title: Mind Trap
summary: The second release for Turner Prize-winning artist was co-produced with Andy Knowles and Nick McCarthy.

title: Chocolate Factory
summary: Beseiged by legal problems (he was arrested in Chicago on child pornography-related charges) and rampant bootlegging of an earlier effort ('Loveland') that forced him to abandon that project, Kelly finally returns with a follow-up to 2000's 'TP-2.Com.'

title: Kicks
summary: The second album for the Scottish band was produced by Bernard Butler and is the first album with Dino Bardot, who replaced Jamie McMorrow.

title: Digi Snacks
summary: The third album for the Wu-Tang Clan member as Bobby Digital features Thea and George Harrison's son as guest artists.

title: Bigfoot
summary: Produced by Richard Swift, the debut release for the indie pop band led by Zach Yudin was influenced by rock of the 1960s and 70s.

title: Gallery [EP]
summary: This seven-track EP from the Northern California indie pop band led by Justin Vallesteros is a follow-up to its 2011 debut full-length, Idle Labor.

title: Don't Act Like You Don't Care
summary: Here We Go Magic's Luke Temple releases his third solo album.

title: Sound City: Real to Reel
summary: The songs on the soundtrack to Dave Grohl's documentary about Sound City Studios (Fleetwood Mac's Rumours, Rage Against The Machine's self-titled debut, Pat Benatar's Crimes of Passion, and Nirvana's Nevermind were recorded there), were composed and recorded with its own 24-hour session using the Neve 8028 recording console from the legendary Los Angeles studio with such artists as Josh Homme, Paul McCartney, Stevie Nicks, Cheap Trick's Rick Nielsen, Trent Reznor, Rick Springfield, Slipknot’s Corey Taylor, Fear's Lee Ving, members of the Foo Fighters, and surviving members of Nirvana.

title: Freedom's Road
summary: The rocker's first album of originals in six years includes the Chevy Trucks themesong "Our Country."

title: Kiss & Tell
summary: The all-female Scandinavian quartet return with a disc produced by Pelle Gunnerfeldt (The Hives), their third album overall and first for new label RCA.

title: La Bella Mafia
summary: The third solo album from the former Junior M.A.F.I.A. member utilizes production and vocal contributions from Swizz Beatz, Missy Elliott, Timbaland and Method Man.

title: Oxeneers Or The Lion Sleeps When Its Antelope Go
summary: The Seattle band (who apparently suffer from either an unusual genetic problem or severe hallucinations) make their full-length debut with this disc.

title: Appeal To Reason
summary: The fifth full-length album for the Chicago punk rock band was produced by Bill Stevenson and Jason Livermore.

title: Better Nature
summary: The fourth full-length studio release for the Los Angeles-based alternative rock band was produced by Jacknife Lee.

title: Love & Devotion
summary: The debut release from Planet Mu founder Mike Paradinas and his wife Lara Rix-Martin features Gravenhurst's Nick Talbot on four tracks.

title: An End Has A Start
summary: The Birmingham, England group tries to escape the sophmore slump and comparisons to other bands with their second album.

title: The Golden Age of Knowhere
summary: The Los Angeles five-piece--named after a song by the Cure--deliver their debut album of catchy punk rock.

title: dios (malos)
summary: Phil Ek produced the second album for the band (formerly known as Dios) fronted by Joel Morales.

title: Superhero Brother
summary: The third album on Jack Johnson's Brushfire label for the Philadelphia trio.

title: Two-Way Mirror
summary: The Los Angeles rock quintet releases its second full-length album produced by Mars Volta's Isaiah "Ikey" Owens.

title: The House
summary: The fourth studio album for the Georgian-born British singer-songwriter was produced by William Orbit.

title: The Hunting Party
summary: The sixth studio release for the nu metal group was co-produced by band members Brad Delson and Mike Shinoda with guest appearances from Page Hamilton, Daron Malakian, Tom Morello, and Rakim.

title: Pagans in Vegas
summary: The sixth full-length studio release for the Canadian indie rock band is its first in three years with another album scheduled for 2016.

title: Temple of I & I
summary: The 10th full-length release for the Washington D.C. electronic duo features guest appearances from Lou Lou Ghelichkhani, Shana Halligan, Raquel Jones, Mr. Lif, Elin Melgarejo, Notch, Puma, and Zee.

title: 9 Dead Alive
summary: Recorded in Mexico by Fermin Vasquez Llera, the first release of new material in five years from Rodrigo Sanchez and Gabriela Quinetro was self-produced.

title: Feelin' Good
summary: The latest release for British DJ George Evelyn includes influences from funk, hip hop, jazz, reggae, and soul music.

title: The  Still Life
summary: The third full-length release for Alessi Laurent-Marke was produced by Andy LeMaster.

title: Free Dimensional
summary: The second electro-pop album from John O'Regan as Diamond Rings was co-produced with Damian Taylor.

title: Into the Murky Water
summary: This is the second album for the British folk rock band twice nominated for the Ivor Novello award for songwriting.

title: Punctuated Equilibrium
summary: Scott "Wino" Weinrich, former member of such bands as The Obsessed, Saint Vitus, Spirit Caravan, Place of Skulls, and The Hidden Hand, releases his debut solo album.

title: Life With You
summary: The Scottish group returns with its seventh studio album.

title: Kevin Michael
summary: Michael's debut album features Wyclef Jean, Lupe Fiasco, Saigon, and Q Tip.

title: Improvisations
summary: The debut full-length collaboration between The Heat's Charles Hayward and Sonic Youth's Thurston Moore was recorded in an afternoon in London.

title: Law Of The Playground
summary: The second album for the English indie-rock duo.

title: Klang
summary: The third album for the British indie-rock band was recorded in Berlin.

title: Court Yard Hounds
summary: The Dixie Chicks' Emily Robison and Martie Maguire record a side project as a duo.

title: The Evolution
summary: The R&B singer's second album is laced with spoken-word interludes. 50 Cent, Lil Jon, and Chamillionaire lend a hand.

title: This Is Gap Dream
summary: The third full-length release for Gabe Fulvimar under the name Gap Dream was recorded over a two year period in California.

title: Those The Brokes
summary: The poppy British quartet are joined by a nine-piece orchestra on their sophomore effort.

title: Outrage! Is Now
summary: The third full-length studio release for the Canadian punk rock duo sees Sebastien Grainger and Jesse F. Keeler dropping the 1979 suffix (which was added in 2004 due to a dispute with DFA Records) from the band name.

title: 99 Cents
summary: The all-girl German group's third disc includes collaborations with Peaches and Miss Kittin, plus a remake of the Tom Tom Club's "Wordy Rappinghood."

title: Under My Skin
summary: Ditching the production team (The Matrix) who made her first album a hit, Lavigne turned to fellow Canadians Chantal Kreviazuk and Raine Maida to write and produce this sophomore disc.

title: Baby Blue
summary: The Boston-based singer-songwriter's second studio album features songs written by Nick Saloman (aka the Bevis Frond), as well as covers of Pink Floyd's "Fearless" and Pete Ham's "Baby Blue."

title: Volcano, I'm Still Excited!!
summary: This self-titled disc marks the debut for the quirky Austin/Brooklyn indie-rock trio, whose guitar-keyboard-drums sound is sometimes reminiscent of Spoon.

title: Politics Of The Business
summary: A veteran of such hip-hop acts as Stetsasonic and Handsome Boy Modeling School and producer of such legendary albums as De La Soul's '3 Feet High and Rising,' Prince Paul returns with his third solo release. Almost a meta-concept album, it is loosely based on Paul's dealings with his (former) record company regarding his previous release, the 1999 concept album 'A Prince Among Thieves.' Among the guests here are Chuck D, Erick Sermon and Ice-T.

title: You Can Play These Songs With Chords
summary: This collection of B-sides, alternate versions and rarities contains 18 tracks, including an early cover of the Smiths' "This Charming Man."

title: The Brave And The Bold
summary: The first collaboration between singer-songwriter Will Oldham and Chicago instrumental post-rockers Tortoise features 10 covers, including takes on songs by Elton John and Bruce Springsteen.

title: Lynn Teeter Flower
summary: The Azure Ray singer's second solo set was recorded with Spoon's Jim Eno and Now It's Overhead's Andy LeMaster as well as Memphis producer Doug Easley. Conor Oberst guests.

title: A Forest of Arms
summary: The sixth studio release for the Canadian folk rock band led by Tony Dekker was partially recorded in Ontario’s Tyendinaga Caverns and Caves.

title: In A Cave
summary: This is the 10th album for the Athens, Georgia, band.

title: Lights
summary: The first full-length album for the British singer-songwriter debuted as number one on the UK album charts. The US version includes three songs not on the UK release.

title: Losst and Founnd
summary: The posthumous release produced by Mark Hudson features contributions from Jim Keltner, Van Dyke Parks, Jimmy Webb, and Harry’s son, Kiefo Nilsson.

title: Prisoner of Conscious
summary: The fifth solo release for the Brooklyn rapper features guest appearances by such artists as Marsha Ambrosius, Busta Rhymes, Curren$y, Melanie Fiona, Kendrick Lamar, Miguel, Nelly, and Seu Jorge.

title: Make Another World
summary: The Scottish rockers fronted by Roddy Woomble reunite with producer Dave Eringa for this follow-up to 2005's 'Warnings/Promises.'

title: Oh Inhuman Spectacle
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the Australian psychedelic rock/pop trio led by Jake Webb.

title: Banks
summary: The second full-length solo album for the Interpol frontman is his first under his real name (he released two albums under the name Julian Plenti).

title: Potato Hole
summary: The first solo album for Booker T in 20 years features Neil Young and the Drive-By Truckers.

title: Vessels
summary: The buzz band from Adelaide, Australia (notable in part due to their twin-drummer lineup) make their full-length debut with this hard-rocking, psychedelic 10-song effort.

title: Luna
summary: The Scottish band that includes three members of the Beta Band releases its sophomore album.

title: Hope
summary: The third full-length release for the Canadian Juno-award winning band was produced by Dave Schiffman.

title: Fifty Shades of Grey [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]
summary: The soundtrack to the film adaptation of E.L. James' book includes songs from AWOLNATION, Beyonce, Danny Elfman, Skylar Grey, Ellie Goulding, Annie Lennox, Sia, The Vaults, Jesse Ware, The Weeknd, Laura Welsh, as well as classics from Frank Sinatra and the Rolling Stones.

title: I Love You Go Easy
summary: The latest album for the Canadian folk singer-songwriter was produced by Sandro Perri.

title: The Straight Hits!
summary: The first new solo release in seven years for the Austin singer-songwriter was written in three days.

title: Get Lost
summary: The Emeralds guitarist releases his second solo album, which includes a nearly 20-minute long track.

title: The Evolution of Man
summary: The fourth release for the British singer/rapper was written while he was in Australia.

title: Replica Sun Machine
summary: The sophomore album for the London-based band was produced by Danger Mouse.

title: Harakiri
summary: The third solo release for the System Of A Down singer was self-produced.

title: Sex Change
summary: The ironic Washington, D.C. post-rockers return with their first album in three years.

title: No Man's Land
summary: The eighth full-length release for the British singer-songwriter features an all-female band for songs about 13 women from history (including his mother) and was produced by Catherine Marks.

title: Take the Crown
summary: Produced by Jacknife Lee, the ninth solo album for the British pop singer is his first since 2009's Reality Killed The Video Star.

title: Sex with an X
summary: The indie-pop legends from Glasgow--that had a well-documented influence on Nirvana frontman, Kurt Cobain--keep at it 20 years since their last release with a new album of upbeat alterna-rock.

title: Contraband
summary: 'Contraband' marks the debut LP for what basically amounts to Scott Weiland (Stone Temple Pilots) fronting Guns N Roses (including Duff McKagan and Slash).

title: A New Morning
summary: Stephen Street is the producer for the Britpop band's catchy fifth album, their first since singer Brett Anderson's recovery from drug problems. Not surprisingly, it is also happier-sounding than previous Suede efforts.

title: Jeff Bridges
summary: Jeff Bridges releases the follow-up album to his debut "Be Here Soon" nearly a decade later, which is produced by T-Bone Burnett.

title: 5 Seconds of Summer
summary: The debut full-length release for the Australian pop-punk quartet includes songs co-written with Yellowcard's Ryan Key, Boys Like Girls' Martin Johnson, All Time Low's Alex Gaskarth, Goldfinger's John Feldmann and Good Charlotte's Benji and Joel Madden.

title: Meyrin Fields
summary: The EP from the James Mercer and Brian Burton duo includes tracks not released on their self-titled album.

title: Megaplex
summary: The sixth full-length release for the New York indie pop duo was produced by Max Hart.

title: The Breeze: An Appreciation of J.J. Cale
summary: The tribute to JJ Cale by Eric Clapton features performances by Mark Knopfler, Christine Lakeland, John Mayer, Willie Nelson, Tom Petty, Derek Trucks, and Don White.

title: Storm & Grace
summary: The third studio album for Lisa Marie Presley was produced by T-Bone Burnett and is her first on the Universal Republic label.

title: Shiny and Oh So Bright, Vol. 1: No Past. No Future. No Sun
summary: Produced by Rick Rubin, the 10th full-length release for the alternative rock band sees the return of original members Jimmy Chamberlin and James Iha, joining remaining members Billy Corgan and Jeff Schroeder.

title: Mission Bell
summary: The fourth album for the singer-songwriter features appearances by Priscilla Ahn, Pieta Brown, James Gadson, Willie Nelson, Lucinda Williams, Iron & Wine's Sam Beam, and Calexico.

title: Is That You in the Blue?
summary: With Dexter on guitar and his sister Sara on drums, the band releases its sophomore album of blues, jazz, psychobilly ballads, pop songs, and more.

title: Detroit House Guests
summary: The seventh full-length release for the husband-and-wife duo of Adam Lee Miller and Nicola Kuperus features guest appearances from Robert Aiki Aubrey Lowe, Dorit Chrysler, Light Asylum's Shannon Funchess, Swans' Michael Gira, Nitzer Ebb's Douglas J. McCarthy, and Lun*na Menoh.

title: Wildlife
summary: This is the third full-length studio album for the rock band from Illinois.

title: The Destroyed Room: B-Sides And Rarities
summary: Not the most accessible (sound-wise) of Sonic Youth's releases, this 11-track disc compiles some of the least accessible (availability-wise) of the band's obscure recordings, which have been remastered.

title: KEYS
summary: Produced with Mike WiLL Made-It, the two-disc release from R&B artist Alicia Keys features piano-based originals and more upbeat versions with drums.

title: Anyway You Love, We Know How You Feel
summary: The fourth full-length studio release for the blues rock band was self-produced and is its first with new drummer Tony Leone.

title: Summer of '13
summary: The first new solo release for the Scottish artist under his real name in seven years features contributions from De Rosa's Martin John Henry, First Aid Kit drummer Scott Simpson and Beta Band's Gordon Anderson.

title: Save Your Season
summary: This is the second release for the husband and wife team of Keith and Hollie Kenniff.

title: Our Bright Future
summary: The latest album for the Grammy-winning artist was produced with Larry Klein.

title: Made In Sheffield
summary: The man behind the UK hit ‘Is This The Way To Amarillo’ is back with his latest album which features songs written by Richard Hawley, Jarvis Cocker and the Arctic Monkeys' Alex Turner.

title: Cosmic Egg
summary: The second album for the Australian rock band was produced by Alan Moulder.

title: Speed of Darkness
summary: Ryan Hewitt produced the Celtic punk rock band's fifth studio album, which was recorded at a church-turned-recording-studio.

title: Welcome Joy
summary: The second album for the Seattle-based indie rock band was produced by Colin Stewart.

title: Mama, I'm Swollen
summary: The sixth studio album for the Omaha, Nebraska-based indie-rock band.

title: Rise To Your Knees
summary: The rock band reunites (with a new drummer) for a new album.

title: Songs of Patience
summary: The second full-length release for the Brooklyn-based indie rock band led by Petter Ericson Stakee and Terry Wolfers took three years and three producers to make.

title: Art of McCartney
summary: The two-disc tribute album to Paul McCartney songs features such artists as Harry Connick, Jr., Alice Cooper, Roger Daltrey, Def Leppard, Dr. John, Bob Dylan, Barry Gibb, Heart, Billy Joel, Kiss, Jeff Lynne, Steve Miller, Willie Nelson, Corinne Bailey Rae, Smokey Robinson, and Brian Wilson.

title: Best of Times
summary: The third studio release for the British indie rock band led by Ed Wallis was mixed by Larry Crane.

title: Word of Mouth
summary: The seventh release for the British folk artist was recorded in a Cornish church.

title: My Shame Is True
summary: The ninth full-length studio release for the punk rock trio was produced by Bill Stevenson and Jason Livermore.

title: The Duckworth Lewis Method
summary: The debut album for the Irish band formed by Neil Hannon and Thomas Walsh was inspired by the game of cricket.

title: Wonder
summary: The fourth full-length release for the Canadian singer-songwriter features a duet with Justin Bieber.

title: Planet Earth
summary: Prince returns with his 24th studio album--but not without a bit of controversy.

title: Four
summary: The fourth full-length studio release for the London-based pop band features songs co-written by Ed Drewett, Wayne Hector, Jamie Scott, and Ed Sheeran,.

title: Green Imagination
summary: This is the second album for the group led by Bill Doss (formerly of Olivia Tremor Control), which mixes psychedelia and pop.

title: St. Anger
summary: As the title implies, the metal band is just as, well, angry as ever on their first new studio album since 'Load' and 'Reload' appeared in 1996 and 1997. Just don't try downloading it for free--then you'll see some real anger.

title: Love & Distortion
summary: This is the sophomore release for San Francisco's atmospheric noise-pop band led by vocalist Chris Streng, whose previous band shared members with Black Rebel Motorcycle Club.

title: Exciter
summary: This is the first album of new material since 1997's 'Ultra' for Depeche Mode, which again sees the band as a trio (consisting of David Gahan, Martin L. Gore, and Andy Fletcher) but also sees them experimenting more with a wider variety of sounds, including acoustic guitar. It is DM's first time in the studio with producer Mark Bell, who has previously worked with Bjork and was a member of the early-90s techno outfit LFO. The lead single from the 13-track album is "Dream On."

title: El Rey
summary: The band led by David Gedge releases its latest album, produced by Steve Albini.

title: X
summary: Kylie returns after her battle with breast cancer with her latest album.

title: Let There Be Morning
summary: 'Morning' marks the U.S. debut for the Swedish four-piece, who originally formed in 1997.

title: Omni
summary: Joe Chiccarelli produced the Seattle-based rock group's fourth album on new label Dangerbird Records.

title: Without Feathers
summary: This long-overdue second album finds the Montreal band shedding its dark, Joy Division-influenced sound for one that more closely resembles classic rock.

title: Different Gear, Still Speeding
summary: With frontman Liam Gallagher taking the reins sans brother Noel, the debut of the Steve Lillywhite-produced album combines psychedelic rock with Beatles-sounding Brit-pop that shows remnants of early Oasis in it's sound.

title: Strange Clouds
summary: The second album for rapper B.o.B. features guest appearances from Morgan Freeman, Taylor Swift, Chris Brown, Lil Wayne, Nicki Minaj, Ryan Tedder, Trey Songz, and T.I.

title: Crush Songs
summary: The debut full-length solo release for the Yeah Yeah Yeahs singer was originally recorded in 2006-07.

title: The Blueprint 3
summary: After seven years, the final album of his Blueprint series is finally released.

title: Greedy Baby
summary: The British electronica duo of Ed Handley and Andy Turner team with visual artist Bob Jaroc for this combination of music and video.

title: Transfixiation
summary: The fourth full-length release for the noise rock band is its first with new drummer Robi Gonzalez.

title: Everybody Loves A Happy Ending
summary: A reunited Curt Smith and Roland Orzabal return with their first Tears For Fears album together in 15 years.

title: R.E.M Live
summary: The first live album for R.E.M. is a recording of the band's Dublin concert in 2005.

title: Gauntlet Hair
summary: The Colorado duo of Andy R. and Craig Nice releases its debut full-length album.

title: Before This World
summary: The first release of original material from the multiple Grammy winning singer-songwriter features a guest appearance from Sting and was produced with Dave O'Donnell.

title: Success
summary: The sixth full-length release for the Canadian noise rock trio was produced by Steve Albini.

title: Quarters
summary: The debut full-length studio release for British electronic producer James Welch was recorded in four different locations in Berlin.

title: Kiss Land
summary: After a trilogy of mixtapes, the Canadian artist releases his debut studio release that includes a guest appearance from Drake.

title: All Hell Breaks Loose
summary: The debut release for the hard rock band formed by Thin Lizzy guitarist Scott Gorham with Ricky Warwick, Jimmy DeGrasso, Marco Mendoza, and Damon Johnson was produced by Kevin Shirley.

title: Candela
summary: The seventh release for the band led by Adam Pierce sees the group adding more pop elements to the other music styles heard on previous albums.

title: This Is Christmas
summary: Ash singer Tim Wheeler and his singer/songwriter girlfriend, Emmy the Great, wrote this album of Christmas songs after being trapped at an airport by a snowstorm.

title: In the Grace of Your Love
summary: The New York trio releases their fourth album of dance punk.
This is the debut album for the Brooklyn-based trio.

title: A Guide to Love, Loss & Desperation
summary: The debut album from the three-piece from Liverpool, England.

title: There's No 666 In Outer Space
summary: The Sacramento duo has transformed into a full five-piece band, fronted by new singer Aaron Ross, for this new LP.

title: 4:21 ... The Day After
summary: The Wu-Tang star's fourth solo album includes contributions from Ol' Dirty Bastard, RZA, Ginuwine and Raekwon.

title: It Ain't Safe No More
summary: Busta is back with 19 new tracks, including collaborations with Mariah Carey, Carl Thomas and The Neptunes.

title: Mind Elevation
summary: The British techno pioneer(s) (now down to just one founding member, George Evelyn), return with their first studio album in three years.

title: Strange Little Girls
summary: Yes, it is a covers album, but with a bit of a twist: all the songs were originally written and performed by men, and Amos has reinterpreted them from a woman's standpoint. This eclectic collection (12 tracks in all) includes versions of Depeche Mode's "Enjoy The Silence," Eminem's "97' Bonnie and Clyde," 10cc's "I'm Not In Love," Neil Young's "Heart Of Gold," Slayer's "Raining Blood," and the Boomtown Rats' "I Don't Like Mondays."

title: Hard Candy
summary: The queen of pop's latest and last release on the Warner Brothers label was produced in part by Nate "Danja" Hills, Timbaland, Justin Timberlake, and Pharrell Williams.

title: Pocketful of Sunshine
summary: The sophomore album for the English singer.

title: The Alchemy Index Vols. I and II: Fire and Water
summary: The first of two volumes of EPs produced by their guitarist Teppei Teranishi.

title: Wanderlust
summary: The fifth full-length release for the British indie singer was co-written and produced by Ed Harcourt.

title: Konk
summary: The sophomore album was produced by Tony Hoffer. The British band recently lost its bassist Max Rafferty, who quit earlier this year.

title: Forever
summary: This is the debut full-length release for the San Francisco-based cousins Reese Donohue and Christopher Prudhomme.

title: L.A.X.
summary: The third album for the rapper from California features guest artists such as Common, Ice Cube, Lil Wayne, Ludacris, Nas, Ne-Yo, and Travis Barker.

title: From the Hills Below the City
summary: The debut release for the folk rock quartet from New Albany, Indiana (near Louisville, Kentucky) was produced by Kevin Ratterman.

title: Here I Stand
summary: The fifth album for the R&B singer features Young Jeezy, will.i.am, Jay-Z, Jermaine Dupri, Beyoncé, and Lil Wayne.

title: Native
summary: This is the third full-length studio release for the pop rock band led by singer-songwriter/producer Ryan Tedder.

title: Avril Lavigne
summary: The fifth full-length studio release for the Canadian pop singer features songs co-written with her husband, Chad Kroeger of Nickelback.
